{"title_page": "Hammer Museum", "text_new": "{{for|the collection of hammers|Hammer Museum (Haines, Alaska)}}\n{{Infobox Museum\n|name          = Hammer Museum\n|image         = Wdmk HammerBox Black.jpg\n|map_type      =\n|map_caption   = \n|latitude      =\n|longitude     =\n|established   = 1990\n|dissolved     =\n|location      = 10899 [[Wilshire Boulevard]], Los Angeles, California 90024 (by UCLA campus)\n|coordinates   = {{coord|34|3|34|N|118|26|37|W|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|type          = [[Art museum]], [[University of California, Los Angeles]] ([[UCLA]])\n|visitors      =\n|director      = [[Ann Philbin]]\n|publictransit =\n|website       = {{url|http://www.hammer.ucla.edu/}}\n}}\nThe '''Hammer Museum''', which is affiliated with the [[University of California, Los Angeles]], is an [[art museum]] and [[cultural center]] known for its artist-centric and progressive array of exhibitions and public programs. Founded in 1990 by the entrepreneur-industrialist [[Armand Hammer]] to house his personal art collection, the museum has since expanded its scope to become \"the hippest and most culturally relevant institution in town.\"<ref name=\"LATM-tastemaker\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.latimesmagazine.com/2009/07/ann-philbin-tastemaker.html |title=Tastemakers 2009: Ann Philbin |first=Greg |last=Cerio |date=2009 |magazine=[[Los Angeles Times Magazine]] |accessdate=April 6, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514154155/http://www.latimesmagazine.com/2009/07/ann-philbin-tastemaker.html |archivedate=May 14, 2011}}</ref> Particularly important among the museum's critically acclaimed exhibitions are presentations of both historically over-looked and emerging contemporary artists. The Hammer Museum also hosts over 300 programs throughout the year, from lectures, symposia, and readings to concerts and film screenings. As of February 2014, the museum's collections, exhibitions, and programs are completely free to all visitors.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2014/feb/07/entertainment/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-free-admission-sunday-20140207 |title=Hammer Museum to offer free admission starting Sunday |first=David |last=Ng |date=February 7, 2014 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306205120/http://articles.latimes.com/2014/feb/07/entertainment/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-free-admission-sunday-20140207 |archive-date=March 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/about-us/ |title=About Us |website=Hammer Museum |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"knight-hammer\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-knight-hammer-notebook-20131007-story.html |title=UCLA Hammer Museum embraces free admission, and it has company |first=Christopher |last=Knight |date=October 6, 2013 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n\nThe Hammer opened November 28, 1990 with an exhibition of work by the Russian [[Suprematist]] painter [[Kazimir Malevich]] which originated at the [[National Gallery of Art]] in Washington and subsequently travelled to the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York.<ref name=\"LAT-Litigation\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-01-25/entertainment/ca-701_1_armand-hammer-museum |title=Confused Picture at Hammer Museum : Litigation, Lack of Direction Cloud Future of Recently Opened Westwood Facility |last=Parachini |first=Allan |date=January 25, 1991 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612075857/http://articles.latimes.com/1991-01-25/entertainment/ca-701_1_armand-hammer-museum |archive-date=June 12, 2017}}</ref> The museum has since presented important single-artist and thematic exhibitions of historical and [[contemporary art]]. It has developed an international reputation for reintroducing artists and movements that have often been overlooked in the art historical canon.<ref name=\"NYT-Sheets\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/10/06/arts/design/06hamm.html |title=Armand Hammer's Orphan Museum Turns Into Cinderella in Los Angeles |last=Sheets |first=Hilarie M. |date=October 6, 2004 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> Notable examples include a 2003 retrospective of [[Lee Bontecou]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2003/lee-bontecou/ |title=Lee Bontecou |date=2003 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> co-organized with the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago]]; ''Heat Waves in a Swamp: The Paintings of Charles Burchfield'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2009/heat-waves-in-a-swamp-the-paintings-of-charles-burchfield/ |title=Heat Waves in a Swamp: The Paintings of Charles Burchfield |date=2009 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> curated by the artist [[Robert Gober]]; and ''Now Dig This!: Art and Black Los Angeles, 1960\u20131980'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2011/now-dig-this-art-and-black-los-angeles-1960-1980/ |title=Now Dig This!: Art and Black Los Angeles 1960\u20131980 |date=2011 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> the Hammer Museum's contribution to the Getty's 2011 Pacific Standard Time initiative. The Hammer is dedicated to diversity and inclusion. Of all of the solo exhibitions on view in Los Angeles between January 2008 and December 2012, the Hammer is the only institution to devote 50% of its exhibition programming to female artists.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-women-artist-20130711,0,6560536.story |title=LACMA, MOCA fall behind in giving female artists a solo platform |last=Knight |first=Christopher |date=July 11, 2013 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130712151427/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-women-artist-20130711,0,6560536.story |archive-date=July 12, 2013}}</ref> The Hammer also hosts roughly fifteen Hammer Projects each year, offering international and local artists a laboratory-like surrounding to create new and innovative work.\n\n===Los Angeles Biennial: ''Made in L.A.''===\nIn 2010 the Hammer announced its inaugural biennial devoted exclusively to Los Angeles artists.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/07/entertainment/la-et-hammer-biennial-20100907 |title=L.A. art biennial on tap for 2012 |last=Finkel |first=Jori |date=September 7, 2010 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306195228/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/07/entertainment/la-et-hammer-biennial-20100907 |archive-date=March 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/25/entertainment/la-ca-hammer-biennial-made-in-la-20120527 |title=Hammer biennial lends artists a helping hand |last=Finkel |first=Jori |date=May 25, 2012 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180307101603/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/25/entertainment/la-ca-hammer-biennial-made-in-la-20120527 |archive-date=March 7, 2018}}</ref> Though the museum has routinely featured California artists as part of its ongoing exhibition program, the ''Made in L.A.'' series has emerged as an important and high-profile platform to showcase the diversity and energy of Los Angeles as an emerging art capitol. Organized by Hammer senior curator Anne Ellegood, Hammer curator Ali Subotnick, LAXART director and chief curator Lauri Firstenberg, LAXART associate director and senior curator Cesar Garcia, and LAXART curator-at-large Malik Gaines, the inaugural ''Made in L.A.'' in 2012<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2012/made-in-la-2012/ |title=Made in L.A. 2012 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> featured work by 60 Los Angeles artists in spaces throughout the city including the Hammer Museum itself, LAXART, and the [[Los Angeles Municipal Art Gallery]] in [[Barnsdall Art Park]]. In conjunction with the exhibition, the Hammer also sponsored a satellite exhibition, the Venice Beach Biennial on the Venice Boardwalk, between July 13 and 15th of that year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.madeinla2012.org/visit/#venice-beach |title=General Info |website=Made in L.A. 2012 |accessdate=April 1, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407080556/http://www.madeinla2012.org/visit/ |archivedate=April 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe second iteration of ''Made in L.A.'' in 2014<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/made-in-la-2014/ |title=Made in L.A. 2014 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> took over the entire space of the museum to feature work by more than 30 different artists and collectives. The 2014 exhibition was organized by Hammer chief curator Connie Butler and independent curator Michael Ned Holte.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/21/arts/design/two-big-collectors-ready-for-november.html |title=Two Big Collectors Ready for November |last=Vogel |first=Carol |date=September 20, 2012 |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn conjunction with the inaugural ''Made in L.A.'' exhibition in 2012, the Hammer offered the first iteration of the prestigious Mohn Award to the artist [[Meleko Mokgosi]]. The award consisted of a catalogue and a $100,000 cash prize and was decided by public vote after a jury of experts narrowed the 60 participants to five finalists.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/aug/16/entertainment/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-mohn-prize-to-meleko-mokgosi-20120816 |title=Hammer Museum's $100,000 Mohn Award goes to painter Meleko Mokgosi |last=Finkel |first=Jori |date=August 16, 2012 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220050203/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/aug/16/entertainment/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-mohn-prize-to-meleko-mokgosi-20120816 |archive-date=February 20, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/culturemonster/2012/03/hammer-prize-new-biennial.html |title=Hammer announces $100,000 prize for new biennial; 60 artists chosen |last=Finkel |first=Jori |date=March 14, 2012 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> The Mohn Award, funded by Los Angeles philanthropists and art collectors Jarl and Pamela Mohn and the Mohn Family Foundation, was one of the most generous international awards given to a single artist.\n\nIn 2014 the Hammer announced it was offering three awards in conjunction with ''Made in L.A. 2014'': The Mohn Award ($100,000), the Career Achievement Award ($25,000)\u2014both of which are selected by a professional jury\u2014and the Public Recognition Award ($25,000), which is awarded by popular vote among exhibition visitors. All three awards are again funded by Jarl and Pamela Mohn and the Mohn Family Foundation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.laweekly.com/publicspectacle/2014/01/30/hammer-museums-controversial-mohn-award-returns-with-a-twist |title=Hammer Museum's Controversial Mohn Award Returns \u2013 With a Twist |last=Cheh |first=Carol |date=January 30, 2014 |newspaper=[[LA Weekly]] |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref> In 2014 [[Alice K\u00f6nitz]]'s Los Angeles Museum on Art won the Mohn Award, [[California Clay Movement#pupils|Michael Frimkess]] and Magdalena Suarez Frimkess were awarded the Career Achievement Award, and [[Jennifer Moon]] was awarded the Public Recognition Award.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-made-in-la-awards-winners-20140818-story.html |title=Hammer Museum announces winners of 2014 Made in L.A. Mohn Awards |first=Jessica |last=Gelt |date=August 19, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.laweekly.com/arts/jennifer-moon-wins-hammer-museum-award-plans-to-start-revolution-5018046 |title=Jennifer Moon Wins Hammer Museum Award, Plans to Start Revolution |last=Swann |first=Jennifer |date=August 20, 2014 |newspaper=LA Weekly |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Collections==\nThe Hammer Museum manages five distinct collections: The Hammer Contemporary Collection;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/collections/hammer-contemporary-collection/ |title=Hammer Contemporary Collection |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> the collection of the UCLA Grunwald Center for the Graphic Arts;<ref name=\"grunwald-center\">{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/collections/grunwald-center-collection/ |title=Grunwald Center for the Graphic Arts |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> the Franklin D. Murphy Sculpture Garden;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/collections/franklin-d-murphy-sculpture-garden/ |title=Franklin D. Murphy Sculpture Garden |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> the Armand Hammer Collection,<ref name=\"armand-hammer\">{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/collections/armand-hammer-collection/ |title=Armand Hammer Collection |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> and the Armand Hammer Daumier and Contemporaries Collection.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/collections/armand-hammer-daumier-and-contemporaries-collection/ |title=Armand Hammer Daumier and Contemporaries Collection |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Hammer Contemporary Collection===\nThe Hammer Contemporary Collection, inaugurated in 1999, is the museum's growing collection of modern and contemporary art. The collection includes works on paper, primarily drawings and photographs, as well as paintings, sculpture, and media arts. The Contemporary Collection houses works from artists, including many active in Southern California from 1960 to the present. Hammer Contemporary Collection works are often acquired in tandem with exhibitions presented at the museum, including the Hammer Projects series focusing on the work of emerging artists.\n\nThe 2009 exhibition Second Nature: The Valentine-Adelson Collection<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2009/second-nature-the-valentine-adelson-collection-at-the-hammer/ |title=Second Nature: The Valentine-Adelson Collection at the Hammer |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> at the Hammer exhibited selections from Dean Valentine and Amy Adelson's gift to the Hammer Contemporary Collection. The gift of fifty sculptures by 29 Los Angeles artists represents a significant milestone in the Hammer's commitment to collecting the works of Southern California artists.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2005/thing/ |title=Thing: New Sculpture from Los Angeles |date=2005 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the Hammer showcased selections from the Susan and Larry Marx Collection.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2012/intimate-immensity-the-susan-and-larry-marx-collection/ |title=Susan and Larry Marx Collection |date=2012 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> The exhibition was made possible by a substantial gift from longtime museum supporters Susan and Larry Marx and includes more than 150 paintings, sculptures, and works on paper by over 100 international artists from the post-World War II period. The collection includes examples of Abstract Expressionism on canvas and paper by the American artists [[Jackson Pollock]], [[Willem de Kooning]], and Philip Guston as well as works by contemporary artists including Mark Bradford, Rachel Whiteread, Mary Heilmann, and Mark Grotjahn among others.\n\nHighlights from the contemporary collection include: ''The Battle of Atlanta: Being the Narrative of a Negress in the Flames of Desire - A Reconstruction'' (1995) by Kara Walker, Untitled (2007) by [[Mark Bradford]], Migration (2008) by [[Doug Aitken]], Untitled #5 (2010) by [[Lari Pittman]], Mirage (2011) by Katie Grinnan, Ruby I (2012) by Mary Weatherford, Mimus Act I (2012) by [[Mary Kelly (artist)|Mary Kelly]].\n\nNotable recent acquisitions to the Hammer Contemporary Collection include [[Suzanne Lacy]]'s ''Three Weeks in May'' (1977), as well as major works by [[Lisa Anne Auerbach]], [[Fiona Connor]], Bruce Connor, Jeremy Deller, [[Jessica Jackson Hutchins]], Friedrich Kunath, [[Tala Madani]], Robert Overby, [[Martha Rosler]], [[Sterling Ruby]], [[Allen Ruppersberg]], Barbara T. Smith, William Leavitt, and Eric Wesley.\n\n===UCLA Grunwald Center for the Graphic Arts at the Hammer Museum===\n[[File:Pablo Picasso, 1904, Le repas frugal (The Frugal Repast), etching, Hammer Museum, University of California.jpg|thumb|Pablo Picasso, 1904, ''Le repas frugal'' (''The Frugal Repast''). Printed in 1913. Etching. Plate: 46.7 x 36 cm; Sheet: 65.4 x 47.6 cm]]\nThe UCLA Grunwald Center for the Graphic Arts is one of the most important and comprehensive collections of works on paper in the country. Housed at the Hammer Museum, the center was established in 1956 after a gift from Fred Grunwald and today houses over 40,000 prints, drawings, photographs, and artists' books.<ref name=\"grunwald-center\"/> The collection includes works dating from the Renaissance to the present, including European old master prints and drawings, Japanese ukiyo-e woodblock prints, and a collection of contemporary photography initiated by UCLA photographer Robert Heinecken (1931\u20132006).<ref>{{cite book |title=Catalog of the UCLA Collection of Contemporary American Photographs |last1=Nordland |first1=Gerald |last2=Heinecken |first2=Robert |date=1976 |location=Los Angeles |publisher=Anderson, Ritchie and Simon}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988 the Grunwald Center received a bequest of over 850 landscape drawings and prints from the collection of Los Angeles-based architect Rudolf L. Baumfeld. The Baumfeld Collection includes important examples of European landscapes from the 16th to 20th-centuries and includes pure landscapes, as well as views of architectural ruins and urban scenes.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Rudolf L. Baumfeld Collection of Landscape Drawings & Prints |date=1989 |location=Los Angeles |publisher=The Center}}</ref> The Eunice and Hal David Collection, bequeathed to the Grunwald Center by lyricist Hal David and his wife Eunice,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2003/the-eunice-and-hal-david-collection/ |title=The Eunice and Hal David Collection |date=2003 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref> is a collection of 19th and 20th-century drawings by European and American artists. Selections from the collection were exhibited at the Hammer in 2003.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Eunice and Hal David Collection of Nineteenth and Twentieth-Century Works on Paper |last1=Burlingham |first1=Cynthia |last2=Hendrix |first2=Lee |last3=Brodie |first3=Judith |date=2003 |location=Los Angeles |publisher=UCLA Grunwald Center for the Graphic Arts, UCLA Hammer Museum}}</ref> The 2014 exhibition<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2014/tea-and-morphine-women-in-paris-1880-to-1914/ |title=Tea and Morphine: Women in Paris, 1880 to 1914 |date=2014 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref> showcased works from the Elisabeth Dean Collection of 19th and 20th-century works on paper. The collection of approximately 900 prints and illustrated books is among the most significant gifts received by the Grunwald Center in recent years.\n\nThe Grunwald Center is also home to several important collections of Los Angeles-based contemporary artists.<ref>{{cite book |title=Grunwald Center Studies |date=1980 |location=Los Angeles |publisher=Grunwald Center for the Graphic Arts}}</ref> The Grunwald Center's collection features over 1,000 works by Sister [[Corita Kent]], an influential pop printmaker and social justice activist, including rare preparatory studies and sketchbooks.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-11-07/entertainment/ca-923_1_corita-kent |title=Documentary Remembers Nun and Artist Corita Kent |first=Shauna |last=Snow |date=November 7, 1989 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307232424/http://articles.latimes.com/1989-11-07/entertainment/ca-923_1_corita-kent |archive-date=March 7, 2016}}</ref> Additionally, the Grunwald maintains an archive of the first twenty years of [[June Wayne]]'s influential Tamarind Lithography Workshop, offering a rare overview of contemporary print-making in Los Angeles. Jointly acquired by the Grunwald and the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]], the Grunwald Center maintains a complete archive of prints by Los Angeles publisher Edition Jacob Samuel which documents the activity of master intaglio print-maker Jacob Samuel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/blog/2010/04/hammer-lacma-jointly-acquire-archive-of-edition-jacob-samuel/ |title=Hammer & LACMA Jointly Acquire Archive of Edition Jacob Samuel |date=April 27, 2010 |website=Hammer Museum |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref> Highlights from the archive were exhibited in the 2010 exhibition Outside the Box: Edition Jacob Samuel, 1988-2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2010/outside-the-box/ |title=Outside the Box |date=2010 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA research and education resource, the Grunwald Center study room is available by appointment to faculty, students, and members of the public.\n\nHighlights from the Grunwald's collection include: ''Melencolia I'' (1514) by [[Albrecht D\u00fcrer]], ''Christ Preaching'' (1652) by [[Rembrandt van Rijn]], ''Maple trees at Mama, Tekona Shrine and linked Bridge'' (1857) by [[Utagawa Hiroshige]], ''Les Grands Baigneurs'' (1896) by [[Paul C\u00e9zanne]], ''Le Repas Frugal'' (1904) by [[Pablo Picasso]], and ''Entropia (review)'' (2004), by [[Julie Mehretu]].\n\n===Franklin D. Murphy Sculpture Garden===\nThe [[Franklin D. Murphy Sculpture Garden]] at [[UCLA]] was inaugurated in 1967 and dedicated to the [[Franklin David Murphy|eponymous chancellor]] of the university. Designed by famed landscape architect Ralph Cornell, the garden houses over 70 works of modern and contemporary sculpture in a five-acre, park-like setting. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://tclf.org/landscapes/franklin-d-murphy-sculpture-garden |title=Franklin D. Murphy Sculpture Garden |website=The Cultural Landscape Foundation |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tclf.org/news/features/illuminating-los-angeles-design-legacy-ralph-cornell |title=Illuminating the Los Angeles Design Legacy of Ralph Cornell |date=November 17, 2014 |website=The Cultural Landscape Foundation |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://cglhs.org/public-landscapes-ralph-d-cornell/ |title=The Public Landscapes of Ralph D. Cornell |date=November 9, 2014 |website=California Garden Landscape History Society |accessdate=March 6, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617043001/http://cglhs.org/public-landscapes-ralph-d-cornell/ |archive-date=June 17, 2015}}</ref> Group tours of the garden can be scheduled through the Hammer's online request form.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/visit/tours/adult-college-senior-tour-request/ |title=Adult, College & Senior Tour Request |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307153052/http://hammer.ucla.edu/visit/tours/adult-college-senior-tour-request/ |archive-date=March 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe 72 object collection comprises works by Deborah Butterfield, [[Alexander Calder]], [[Henri Matisse]], [[Joan Mir\u00f3]], [[Henry Moore]], [[Isamu Noguchi]], [[Auguste Rodin]], and [[David Smith (sculptor)|David Smith]]. A fully illustrated catalogue, including scholarly entries for each artist, was published by in 2007 by the Hammer Museum.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Franklin D. Murphy Sculpture Garden at UCLA |last=Burlingham |first=Cynthia |date=2007 |location=Los Angeles |publisher=Hammer Museum |isbn=978-0-94373-933-5}}</ref>\n\n===Armand Hammer Collection===\nThe Armand Hammer Collection<ref name=\"armand-hammer\"/> is a small selection of European and American paintings, drawings, and prints that formed the original impetus for the foundation of the Hammer Museum. [[Armand Hammer]], the founder and namesake of the museum, assembled and refined the collection through decades of involvement in the art market, both as a collector in his own right and as a co-founder of Hammer Galleries in New York City.<ref>{{cite book |title=Hammer |last1=Hammer |first1=Armand |last2=Lyndon |first2=Neil |author-link2=Neil Lyndon|date=1987 |location=New York |publisher=Putnam |isbn=978-0-39951-441-8 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/hammerar00hamm }}</ref> The focus of the collection is primarily 19th century and early-20th century French impressionist and post-impressionist paintings, though the collection itself spans the 16th through the 20th century.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Armand Hammer Collection: Five Centuries of Masterpieces |last1=Walker |first1=John |last2=Cain |first2=James Frederick |date=1980 |location=New York |publisher=Abrams |isbn=978-0-81091-069-0}}</ref>\n\nSelections from the collection are on permanent display in the Hammer Museum's third floor galleries, offering patrons a glimpse into some of the most historically relevant movements in Western art. With eminent examples of realism, orientalism, impressionism, and post-impressionism, the collection offers a unique overview of French and American art in the 19th century. Highlights of the collection include: ''Juno'' (ca. 1665-1668) by [[Rembrandt van Rijn]], ''The Education of the Virgin'' (1748-1752) by [[Jean-Honor\u00e9 Fragonard]], ''El Pelele'' (ca. 1791) by [[Francisco Goya]], ''[[Salome Dancing before Herod]]'' (1876) by [[Gustave Moreau]], ''Dr. Pozzi at Home'' (1881) by [[John Singer Sargent]], ''Bonjour Monsieur Gauguin'' (1889) by [[Paul Gauguin]], and ''Hospital at Saint-Remy'' (1889) by [[Vincent van Gogh]].\n\n===Daumier and Contemporaries Collection===\n[[File:Hospital at Saint Remy.jpg|thumb|Vincent van Gogh. ''Hospital at Saint-R\u00e9my'', 1889. Oil on canvas. 36 5/16 x 28 7/8 in. (92.2 x 73.4 cm). The Armand Hammer Collection, Gift of the Armand Hammer Foundation. Hammer Museum, Los Angeles.]]\n\nThe Honor\u00e9 Daumier and Contemporaries Collection<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/collections/armand-hammer-daumier-and-contemporaries-collection/ |title=Honor\u00e9 Daumier and Contemporaries Collection |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> at the Hammer Museum is one of the most important collections of Daumier works outside France. Housing over 7,500 works of art by the French satirist [[Honor\u00e9 Daumier]] (1808-1879) and other contemporary [[List of caricaturists|caricaturists]], it is the largest of its kind outside of Paris. Daumier, whose life and career spanned the 19th century, was a brilliant [[satire|satirist]] whose works offered incisive comment on the hypocrisies of bourgeois life in the French capital.<ref>{{cite book |title=Honor\u00e9 Daumier 1808-1879: The Armand Hammer Daumier Collection |date=1981 |location=Los Angeles |publisher=Armand Hammer Foundation}}</ref> Daumier was an extremely prolific artist whose work spans multiple media, and as such the collection includes paintings, drawings, lithographs, and a series of bronze portrait busts; all keen examples of Daumier's mordant wit and acerbic attitude towards contemporary politics. Selections from the Daumier and Contemporaries collection are on rotating display alongside works from the Armand Hammer Collection.\n\nHighlights from the Daumier and Contemporaries Collection include Daumier's ''Le pass\u00e9 - Le present - L'avenir'' (1834), ''Un Avocat Plaidant,'' (ca. 1845) ''Nadar \u00e9levant la Photographie \u00e1 la hauteur de l'Art'' (1862), and ''Don Quixote et Sancho Panza'' (1866-1868).\n\n==Programs==\nA diverse range of free public programs are presented at the Hammer Museum six evenings a week throughout the year, including lectures, readings, symposia, film screenings, musical performances, and other events. The [[Billy Wilder]] Theater opened at the Hammer Museum in late 2006, after a $5 million gift from Audrey L. Wilder, the widow of Billy Wilder, enabled the museum to resume building a 300-seat theater left unfinished at Armand Hammer's death.<ref name=\"NYT-Sheets\"/> Its 2006 opening coincided with the centennial of Wilder's birth. The venue currently houses the [[UCLA Film and Television Archive]]'s well-known [[cinematheque]] as well as the Hammer's 300 public programs a year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artinfo.com/galleryguide/20125/6664/about/hammer-museum-los-angeles/ |title=Hammer Museum: About |website=[[Artinfo]] |accessdate=July 11, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706191525/http://www.artinfo.com/galleryguide/20125/6664/about/hammer-museum-los-angeles/ |archivedate=July 6, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nPopular series include a weekly meditation program, the Libros Schmibros book club, and the Hammer Conversations which place major cultural, political, and intellectual leaders in dialog with one another. Past Hammer Conversations participants include the writers [[Joan Didion]], [[Jonathan Lethem]], and [[George Saunders]], the filmmakers [[Atom Egoyan]] and [[Miranda July]], journalist [[Naomi Klein]], comedians [[Jeff Garlin]] and [[Patton Oswalt]], playwright and screenwriter [[David Mamet]], magician [[Ricky Jay]], artists [[Betye Saar]] and [[Sam Durant]], actors [[Leonard Nimoy]] and [[Zachary Quinto]], and many others.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailybruin.com/index.php/blog/spotlight/2011/01/hammer_conversations_program_/ |title=Hammer Conversations program offers insight into philosophies of political artists Tom Morello and Sam Durant |last=Somasundaram |first=Niran |date=January 13, 2011 |newspaper=[[Daily Bruin]] |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref> A striking example of the timeliness and popularity of these events occurred in March 2003, when 2,000 people gathered at the Hammer Museum to hear [[Gore Vidal]] speak about the Iraq war the night before bombing began. Since 2010, the Hammer has partnered with the radio station [[KCRW]] to host an annual outdoor summer concert series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.kcrw.com/musicnews/2010/05/kcrw-hammer-museum-present-the-also-i-like-to-rock-free-concert-series-this-july/ |title=KCRW & Hammer Museum Present the \"Also I Like to Rock\" Free Concert Series This July! |last=Reynolds |first=Rachel |date=May 12, 2010 |website=[[KCRW]] Music Blog |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the past, the Hammer traditionally focused on university-level education programs because of its affiliation with UCLA.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/16/entertainment/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-anthony-pritzker-20130915 |title=Hammer Museum gets $2-million gift from Anthony Pritzker |last=Ng |first=David |date=September 16, 2013 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113053702/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/16/entertainment/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-anthony-pritzker-20130915 |archive-date=January 13, 2016}}</ref> Since 2009, the Hammer has been annually inviting an accomplished group of Los Angeles artists to lead workshops based on their working processes on the occasion of the Kids' Art Museum Project (K.A.M.P). Unlike other family events, K.A.M.P. provides access and experiences for children and their families with renowned Los Angeles artists, many of whom have been the subject of exhibitions at the Hammer Museum. Past participating artists include [[Edgar Arceneaux]], [[Mark Grotjahn]], [[Catherine Opie]], [[Jorge Pardo (artist)|Jorge Pardo]], and [[Jonas Wood]]. Each year the event features a series of celebrities reading from their favorite children's books in the museum's galleries, such as [[Will Ferrell]], [[Jason Bateman]], [[Hilary Swank]], [[Jodie Foster]] and [[Zoe Saldana]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/julie-bowen-jodie-foster-join-500015 |title=Julie Bowen, Jodie Foster Join Hammer Museum's K.A.M.P. Event |last=Wyrick |first=Christopher |date=May 6, 2013 |newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Hammer Museum Westwood June 2012.jpg|thumb|left|Hammer Museum building in Westwood, Los Angeles]]\nThe museum was founded by [[Armand Hammer]], the late CEO of the [[Occidental Petroleum|Occidental Petroleum Corporation]], as a venue to exhibit his extensive art collection, at the time valued at $250 million.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20098584,00.html |title=Thanks to Medicis Like Norton Simon and Armand Hammer, a Gilded Dilly of An Art Scene Flowers in L.A. |last1=Small |first1=Michael |last2=Savaiano |first2=Jacqueline |date=March 28, 1988 |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303221351/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20098584,00.html |archive-date=March 3, 2016}}</ref> A [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]] board member for nearly 20 years, Hammer withdrew from a non-binding agreement to transfer his paintings to LACMA after disagreements regarding how his collection would be displayed. Shortly thereafter, on January 21, 1988, Hammer announced plans to build his own museum on the site of a Westwood parking garage adjacent to the Occidental headquarters.<ref name=\"LAT-Battle\">{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-05-22/magazine/tm-4568_1_armand-hammer-collection |title=Battle for the Masterpieces : The Armand Hammer-County Museum Deal: A Saga of Art, Power and Big Misunderstandings |first=Robert A. |last=Jones |date=May 22, 1988 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111001914/http://articles.latimes.com/1988-05-22/magazine/tm-4568_1_armand-hammer-collection |archive-date=January 11, 2011}}</ref> Community leaders who hailed the plan as a positive turning point in the neighborhood's development were soon overshadowed by complaints from Occidental shareholders who sued the company over the museum's escalating construction costs, which were capped by a federal judge at $60 million.<ref name=\"LAT-Battle\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-01-28/news/we-39037_1_armand-hammer-museum |title=Westwood Village Pins Hopes for Renaissance on Hammer Museum |first=Philipp |last=Gollner |date=January 28, 1988 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305212715/http://articles.latimes.com/1988-01-28/news/we-39037_1_armand-hammer-museum |archive-date=March 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-02-21/entertainment/ca-1119_1_armand-hammer-museum |title=Armand Hammer Museum: Who Paid for What? : Art: Internal Occidental documents indicate that officials may have transferred millions of dollars to other corporate accounts to meet budget goal |first=Allan |last=Parachini |date=February 21, 1990 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106031637/http://articles.latimes.com/1990-02-21/entertainment/ca-1119_1_armand-hammer-museum |archive-date=January 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-02-22/entertainment/ca-1803_1_hammer-museum |title=Dissident Shareholder Claims Oxy Falsified Museum Books |first=Allan |last=Parachini |date=February 22, 1990 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180515094317/http://articles.latimes.com/1990-02-22/entertainment/ca-1803_1_hammer-museum |archive-date=May 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDesigned by Edward Larrabee Barnes, the New York-based architect responsible for the Dallas Museum of Art and the Walker Art Center, the building housing the museum was conceived as a Renaissance palazzo with galleries centered around a tranquil, interior courtyard and a relatively austere exterior profile.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-01-13/realestate/re-94_1_hammer-museum |title=Critique : Hammer's Modest Museum |first=Leon |last=Whiteson |date=January 13, 1991 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170409021604/http://articles.latimes.com/1991-01-13/realestate/re-94_1_hammer-museum |archive-date=April 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, architect [[Michael Maltzan]] designed the [[Billy Wilder]] Theater and the museum's caf\u00e9. Michael Maltzan Architecture also designed the John V. Tunney Bridge, which opened in February 2015. The pedestrian bridge, named in honor of [[John V. Tunney]], longtime Chairman of the Board of Directors of the Hammer Museum, connects the upper level galleries over the Hammer Courtyard.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-bridge-michael-maltzan-20141119-story.html |title=Courtyard bridge by Michael Maltzan to open at Hammer in February |first=Jessica |last=Gelt |date=November 19, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHammer died less than a month after his namesake museum opened to the public in November 1990, leaving the fledgling institution mired in litigation over its financing and prompting new legal battles regarding the disposition of Hammer's estate. While the museum's operating budget was provided by a $36 million annuity purchased by [[Occidental Petroleum]], questions remained regarding the future of the museum's collections and the role that the Hammer family would play in its administration.<ref name=\"LAT-Litigation\"/> In 1994, the Regents of the University of California entered into a 99-year operating agreement with the Armand Hammer Foundation to assume management of the museum, which afforded the fledgling institution a measure of stability. At that point the exhibition programs of the Wight Art Gallery, UCLA's existing museum, and the Grunwald Center for the Graphic Arts, the university's print collection, were moved to the Hammer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arts.ucla.edu/press/pdf/UCLAArtsHistory.pdf |title=UCLA Arts History |date=July 23, 2008 |website=UCLA School of the Arts & Architecture |accessdate=March 6, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123033139/https://www.arts.ucla.edu/press/pdf/UCLAArtsHistory.pdf/ |archive-date=January 23, 2015}}</ref> A 2007 a settlement between the UC Regents and the Hammer Foundation formally ended long-simmering disputes over the Hammer collection's ownership and established new guidelines for its display that allowed the museum more space for exhibitions and a growing contemporary collection.<ref name=\"LAT-Divided\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2007/jan/19/entertainment/et-hammer19 |title=Hammer divided yet strong |first=Suzanne |last=Muchnic |authorlink=Suzanne Muchnic |date=January 19, 2007 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 19, 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306032652/http://articles.latimes.com/2007/jan/19/entertainment/et-hammer19 |archive-date=March 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDespite the institutional hurdles that earned it the nickname \"America's vainest museum\" at its inception, the Hammer is now widely acknowledged as \"a hot spot for contemporary art and ideas and a venue for serious exploration of overlooked historical subjects.\" Under current leadership, the Hammer's budget has grown from $5 million to roughly $20 million annually, with a full-time staff of over 100.<ref name=\"LAT-Striking\">{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-ca-philbin18-2009oct18-story.html |title=The Hammer Museum's striking rise |first=Suzanne |last=Muchnic |date=October 18, 2009 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324115719/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-ca-philbin18-2009oct18-story.html |archive-date=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-Life-Support\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/23/arts/design/hurdles-grow-at-the-museum-of-contemporary-art-los-angeles.html |title=A Los Angeles Museum on Life-Support |first=Roberta |last=Smith |date=July 22, 2012 |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, amidst the [[Coronavirus pandemic]], the museum was temporary closed and laid off its 150 part-time student employees.<ref name=\"LAT-Hammer-Covid\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/story/2020-03-25/hammer-museum-layoffs-student-employees |title=Hammer Museum lays off 150 student employees |first=Deborah |last=Vankin |date=March 25, 2020 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Management==\n\n===Directors===\nIn 1994, Henry Hopkins, then director of the Wight gallery and professor in the Department of Art at UCLA, became director of the Museum. He served in that position until his retirement in 1998.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/arts/la-me-henry-hopkins29-2009sep29,0,6304306.story |title=Henry T. Hopkins dies at 81; painter and museum director had formative role in L.A. art scene |last=Muchnic |first=Suzanne |date=September 28, 2009 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091026164048/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/arts/la-me-henry-hopkins29-2009sep29,0,6304306.story |archive-date=October 26, 2009}}</ref> In 1999 [[Ann Philbin]], previously director of [[The Drawing Center]] in New York, was named director and still serves as director today.\n\n===Board of Directors and Board of Overseers===\n\nThe Hammer Museum was founded by Dr. Armand Hammer. [[Michael Armand Hammer]] is Chairman Emeritus, and [[Armie Hammer]] and Viktor Armand Hammer are Honorary Directors. Michael Rubel serves as President, Nelson C. Rising serves as Vice President, and Steven A. Olsen serves as Treasurer. Under Chair [[Marcy Carsey]], the Hammer's Board of Directors also includes Heather R. Axe, Ren\u00e9e Becnel, [[Gene Block]], Lloyd E. Cotsen, [[Eric Esrailian]], Erika J. Glazer, Manuela Herzer, Larry Marx, [[Anthony Pritzker]], Lee Ramer, Kevin L. Ratner, Chip Rosenbloom, Steven P. Song, John V. Tunney, [[Kevin Wall]], John Walsh, and Christopher A. Waterman.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/about-us/museum-boards/ |title=Boards and Governance |website=Hammer Museum |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref> Members of the Board of Overseers include artists [[Barbara Kruger]] and [[Lari Pittman]]. The museum does not disclose its annual board membership dues.\n\n===Funding===\nIn 1994, the [[Regents of the University of California]] entered into a 99-year operating agreement with the Armand Hammer Foundation<ref name=\"LAT-Divided\"/> and assumed management of the Hammer Museum, with the foundation retaining some control, including a \"reversionary clause,\"<ref name=\"LAT-Striking\"/> granting the foundation rights to reclaim the art collection and some of the endowment funds. The museum had long desired to eliminate these clauses. Operating money came from a bond portfolio, UCLA's existing art budgets, private donations, and revenue from the museum.<ref name=\"LAT-Striking\"/> In 2009, the museum operates on an annual operating budget of $14 million, 10% to 12% of which comes from the university. By the fiscal year 2011, its budget of $16 million surpassed that of the much larger [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"NYT-Life-Support\"/>\n\t\nOn January 19, 2007 the Hammer Museum and the Armand Hammer Foundation agreed to dissolve their relationship, dividing the remaining 195 objects which founded the museum; the foundation retaining 92 paintings valued at $55 million, while the museum retaining 103 objects, valued at $250 million. By 2020, the museum will use its bond portfolio, valued at about $55 million, to purchase the building that houses the museum and Occidental's former headquarters.<ref name=\"LAT-Striking\"/>\n\nIn addition, the Hammer Museum's annual Gala in the Garden serves as a fundraiser for the museum. The 2019 edition raised $2.7 million.<ref>Jori Finkel (October 15, 2019), [https://www.theartnewspaper.com/blog/i-can-divide-my-life-into-before-and-after-judy-chicago-gloria-steinem-reveals-how-the-artist-changed-her-thoughts-about-art-at-hammer-museum-gala \u2018I can divide my life into before and after Judy Chicago\u2019: Gloria Steinem reveals how the artist changed her thoughts about art at Hammer Museum gala] ''[[The Art Newspaper]]''.</ref> Recent museum honorees include [[Robert Gober]], [[Tony Kushner]], [[Barbara Kruger]] and [[Cindy Sherman]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-diane-keaton-paul-mccarthy-hammer-museum-20150520-story.html |title=Diane Keaton, Paul McCarthy to be honored at Hammer Museum |last=Ng |first=David |date=May 20, 2015 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Attendance===\nAt the Hammer Museum, 2010 attendance was an estimated 175,000, up from 150,000 in 2009.<ref name=\"JoriFinkel-2011\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/mar/30/entertainment/la-et-museum-attendance-2-20110329/2 |title=Attendance at L.A. museums lags behind |last=Finkel |first=Jori |date=March 30, 2011 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=6 March 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106080240/http://articles.latimes.com/2011/mar/30/entertainment/la-et-museum-attendance-2-20110329/2 |archive-date=November 6, 2012}}</ref> As of 2013, annual attendance for permanent collection, special exhibitions and programs stands at about 200,000.<ref name=\"knight-hammer\"/> The museum does not provide exact figures as it does not have a computerized ticketing system.<ref name=\"JoriFinkel-2011\"/> According to the museum's director Ann Philbin, the museum has \"defined our primary audience as artists\".<ref name=\"LATM-tastemaker\"/> Visitor numbers are also not limited to the Hammer's own box office but might also include people around the world who log on to the museum's Web site to view podcasts of public programs, or visit travelling exhibitions which the Hammer organized.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/08/arts/design/08museum.html |title=Sketching a Future for Brooklyn Museum |last=Pogrebin |first=Robin |date=August 5, 2010 |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Deaccessioning===\nIn 1994, the Hammer Museum made headlines by selling [[Leonardo da Vinci|Leonardo da Vinci's]] [[Codex Leicester]] to [[Microsoft]] founder [[Bill Gates]] for $30.8 million. The Codex Leicester was one of Dr. Hammer's proudest acquisitions, purchased in 1980 for $5.12 million, and one which he unsuccessfully tried to rename the ''Codex Hammer''.<ref name=\"Time1991\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,972206,00.html |title=America's Vainest Museum |last=Hughes |first=Robert |author-link=Robert Hughes (critic) |date=January 28, 1991 |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]] |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> Most museums have [[Collection (museum)|collection]] guidelines for deaccessing art, which require the revenue from sales to be used for future acquisitions. The Hammer Museum alternatively sold the 72-page scientific notebook to fund the museum's exhibitions and programs.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite news |url=http://www.calendarlive.com/printedition/calendar/cl-et-hammer15jan15,0,5571996.story?coll=cl-calendar |first1=Christopher |last1=Reynolds |first2=Hugh |last2=Hart |title=The Da Vinci codex versus the museum code |date=January 15, 2007 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=January 15, 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070117115447/http://www.calendarlive.com/printedition/calendar/cl-et-hammer15jan15,0,5571996.story?coll=cl-calendar |archive-date=January 17, 2007}}\n* {{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2007/jan/22/entertainment/et-hammer22 |title=The Hammer cleanup |first=Christopher |last=Knight |authorlink=Christopher Knight (art critic) |date=January 22, 2007 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 22, 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140515201824/http://articles.latimes.com/2007/jan/22/entertainment/et-hammer22 |archive-date=May 15, 2014}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Hammer Museum}}\n*{{official website|http://www.hammer.ucla.edu/}}\n\n{{UCLA}}\n{{Westwood, Los Angeles}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hammer Museum| ]]\n[[Category:Art museums and galleries in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:University museums in California]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:1990 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 1990]]\n[[Category:Art in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Westwood, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Wilshire Boulevard]]\n[[Category:Edward Larrabee Barnes buildings]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the collection of hammers|Hammer Museum (Haines, Alaska)}}\n{{Infobox Museum\n|name          = Hammer Museum\n|image         = Wdmk HammerBox Black.jpg\n|map_type      =\n|map_caption   = \n|latitude      =\n|longitude     =\n|established   = 1990\n|dissolved     =\n|location      = 10899 [[Wilshire Boulevard]], Los Angeles, California 90024 (by UCLA campus)\n|coordinates   = {{coord|34|3|34|N|118|26|37|W|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|type          = [[Art museum]], [[University of California, Los Angeles]] ([[UCLA]])\n|visitors      =\n|director      = [[Ann Philbin]]\n|publictransit =\n|website       = {{url|http://www.hammer.ucla.edu/}}\n}}\nThe '''Hammer Museum''', which is affiliated with the [[University of California, Los Angeles]], is an [[art museum]] and [[cultural center]] known for its artist-centric and progressive array of exhibitions and public programs. Founded in 1990 by the entrepreneur-industrialist [[Armand Hammer]] to house his personal art collection, the museum has since expanded its scope to become \"the hippest and most culturally relevant institution in town.\"<ref name=\"LATM-tastemaker\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.latimesmagazine.com/2009/07/ann-philbin-tastemaker.html |title=Tastemakers 2009: Ann Philbin |first=Greg |last=Cerio |date=2009 |magazine=[[Los Angeles Times Magazine]] |accessdate=April 6, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514154155/http://www.latimesmagazine.com/2009/07/ann-philbin-tastemaker.html |archivedate=May 14, 2011}}</ref> Particularly important among the museum's critically acclaimed exhibitions are presentations of both historically over-looked and emerging contemporary artists. The Hammer Museum also hosts over 300 programs throughout the year, from lectures, symposia, and readings to concerts and film screenings. As of February 2014, the museum's collections, exhibitions, and programs are completely free to all visitors.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2014/feb/07/entertainment/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-free-admission-sunday-20140207 |title=Hammer Museum to offer free admission starting Sunday |first=David |last=Ng |date=February 7, 2014 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306205120/http://articles.latimes.com/2014/feb/07/entertainment/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-free-admission-sunday-20140207 |archive-date=March 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/about-us/ |title=About Us |website=Hammer Museum |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"knight-hammer\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-knight-hammer-notebook-20131007-story.html |title=UCLA Hammer Museum embraces free admission, and it has company |first=Christopher |last=Knight |date=October 6, 2013 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n\nThe Hammer opened November 28, 1990 with an exhibition of work by the Russian [[Suprematist]] painter [[Kazimir Malevich]] which originated at the [[National Gallery of Art]] in Washington and subsequently travelled to the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York.<ref name=\"LAT-Litigation\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-01-25/entertainment/ca-701_1_armand-hammer-museum |title=Confused Picture at Hammer Museum : Litigation, Lack of Direction Cloud Future of Recently Opened Westwood Facility |last=Parachini |first=Allan |date=January 25, 1991 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612075857/http://articles.latimes.com/1991-01-25/entertainment/ca-701_1_armand-hammer-museum |archive-date=June 12, 2017}}</ref> The museum has since presented important single-artist and thematic exhibitions of historical and [[contemporary art]]. It has developed an international reputation for reintroducing artists and movements that have often been overlooked in the art historical canon.<ref name=\"NYT-Sheets\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/10/06/arts/design/06hamm.html |title=Armand Hammer's Orphan Museum Turns Into Cinderella in Los Angeles |last=Sheets |first=Hilarie M. |date=October 6, 2004 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> Notable examples include a 2003 retrospective of [[Lee Bontecou]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2003/lee-bontecou/ |title=Lee Bontecou |date=2003 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> co-organized with the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago]]; ''Heat Waves in a Swamp: The Paintings of Charles Burchfield'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2009/heat-waves-in-a-swamp-the-paintings-of-charles-burchfield/ |title=Heat Waves in a Swamp: The Paintings of Charles Burchfield |date=2009 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> curated by the artist [[Robert Gober]]; and ''Now Dig This!: Art and Black Los Angeles, 1960\u20131980'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2011/now-dig-this-art-and-black-los-angeles-1960-1980/ |title=Now Dig This!: Art and Black Los Angeles 1960\u20131980 |date=2011 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> the Hammer Museum's contribution to the Getty's 2011 Pacific Standard Time initiative. The Hammer is dedicated to diversity and inclusion. Of all of the solo exhibitions on view in Los Angeles between January 2008 and December 2012, the Hammer is the only institution to devote 50% of its exhibition programming to female artists.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-women-artist-20130711,0,6560536.story |title=LACMA, MOCA fall behind in giving female artists a solo platform |last=Knight |first=Christopher |date=July 11, 2013 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130712151427/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-women-artist-20130711,0,6560536.story |archive-date=July 12, 2013}}</ref> The Hammer also hosts roughly fifteen Hammer Projects each year, offering international and local artists a laboratory-like surrounding to create new and innovative work.\n\n===Los Angeles Biennial: ''Made in L.A.''===\nIn 2010 the Hammer announced its inaugural biennial devoted exclusively to Los Angeles artists.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/07/entertainment/la-et-hammer-biennial-20100907 |title=L.A. art biennial on tap for 2012 |last=Finkel |first=Jori |date=September 7, 2010 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306195228/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/07/entertainment/la-et-hammer-biennial-20100907 |archive-date=March 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/25/entertainment/la-ca-hammer-biennial-made-in-la-20120527 |title=Hammer biennial lends artists a helping hand |last=Finkel |first=Jori |date=May 25, 2012 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180307101603/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/25/entertainment/la-ca-hammer-biennial-made-in-la-20120527 |archive-date=March 7, 2018}}</ref> Though the museum has routinely featured California artists as part of its ongoing exhibition program, the ''Made in L.A.'' series has emerged as an important and high-profile platform to showcase the diversity and energy of Los Angeles as an emerging art capitol. Organized by Hammer senior curator Anne Ellegood, Hammer curator Ali Subotnick, LAXART director and chief curator Lauri Firstenberg, LAXART associate director and senior curator Cesar Garcia, and LAXART curator-at-large Malik Gaines, the inaugural ''Made in L.A.'' in 2012<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2012/made-in-la-2012/ |title=Made in L.A. 2012 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> featured work by 60 Los Angeles artists in spaces throughout the city including the Hammer Museum itself, LAXART, and the [[Los Angeles Municipal Art Gallery]] in [[Barnsdall Art Park]]. In conjunction with the exhibition, the Hammer also sponsored a satellite exhibition, the Venice Beach Biennial on the Venice Boardwalk, between July 13 and 15th of that year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.madeinla2012.org/visit/#venice-beach |title=General Info |website=Made in L.A. 2012 |accessdate=April 1, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407080556/http://www.madeinla2012.org/visit/ |archivedate=April 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe second iteration of ''Made in L.A.'' in 2014<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/made-in-la-2014/ |title=Made in L.A. 2014 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> took over the entire space of the museum to feature work by more than 30 different artists and collectives. The 2014 exhibition was organized by Hammer chief curator Connie Butler and independent curator Michael Ned Holte.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/21/arts/design/two-big-collectors-ready-for-november.html |title=Two Big Collectors Ready for November |last=Vogel |first=Carol |date=September 20, 2012 |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn conjunction with the inaugural ''Made in L.A.'' exhibition in 2012, the Hammer offered the first iteration of the prestigious Mohn Award to the artist [[Meleko Mokgosi]]. The award consisted of a catalogue and a $100,000 cash prize and was decided by public vote after a jury of experts narrowed the 60 participants to five finalists.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/aug/16/entertainment/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-mohn-prize-to-meleko-mokgosi-20120816 |title=Hammer Museum's $100,000 Mohn Award goes to painter Meleko Mokgosi |last=Finkel |first=Jori |date=August 16, 2012 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220050203/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/aug/16/entertainment/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-mohn-prize-to-meleko-mokgosi-20120816 |archive-date=February 20, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/culturemonster/2012/03/hammer-prize-new-biennial.html |title=Hammer announces $100,000 prize for new biennial; 60 artists chosen |last=Finkel |first=Jori |date=March 14, 2012 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> The Mohn Award, funded by Los Angeles philanthropists and art collectors Jarl and Pamela Mohn and the Mohn Family Foundation, was one of the most generous international awards given to a single artist.\n\nIn 2014 the Hammer announced it was offering three awards in conjunction with ''Made in L.A. 2014'': The Mohn Award ($100,000), the Career Achievement Award ($25,000)\u2014both of which are selected by a professional jury\u2014and the Public Recognition Award ($25,000), which is awarded by popular vote among exhibition visitors. All three awards are again funded by Jarl and Pamela Mohn and the Mohn Family Foundation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.laweekly.com/publicspectacle/2014/01/30/hammer-museums-controversial-mohn-award-returns-with-a-twist |title=Hammer Museum's Controversial Mohn Award Returns \u2013 With a Twist |last=Cheh |first=Carol |date=January 30, 2014 |newspaper=[[LA Weekly]] |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref> In 2014 [[Alice K\u00f6nitz]]'s Los Angeles Museum on Art won the Mohn Award, [[California Clay Movement#pupils|Michael Frimkess]] and Magdalena Suarez Frimkess were awarded the Career Achievement Award, and [[Jennifer Moon]] was awarded the Public Recognition Award.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-made-in-la-awards-winners-20140818-story.html |title=Hammer Museum announces winners of 2014 Made in L.A. Mohn Awards |first=Jessica |last=Gelt |date=August 19, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.laweekly.com/arts/jennifer-moon-wins-hammer-museum-award-plans-to-start-revolution-5018046 |title=Jennifer Moon Wins Hammer Museum Award, Plans to Start Revolution |last=Swann |first=Jennifer |date=August 20, 2014 |newspaper=LA Weekly |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Collections==\nThe Hammer Museum manages five distinct collections: The Hammer Contemporary Collection;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/collections/hammer-contemporary-collection/ |title=Hammer Contemporary Collection |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> the collection of the UCLA Grunwald Center for the Graphic Arts;<ref name=\"grunwald-center\">{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/collections/grunwald-center-collection/ |title=Grunwald Center for the Graphic Arts |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> the Franklin D. Murphy Sculpture Garden;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/collections/franklin-d-murphy-sculpture-garden/ |title=Franklin D. Murphy Sculpture Garden |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> the Armand Hammer Collection,<ref name=\"armand-hammer\">{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/collections/armand-hammer-collection/ |title=Armand Hammer Collection |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> and the Armand Hammer Daumier and Contemporaries Collection.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/collections/armand-hammer-daumier-and-contemporaries-collection/ |title=Armand Hammer Daumier and Contemporaries Collection |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Hammer Contemporary Collection===\nThe Hammer Contemporary Collection, inaugurated in 1999, is the museum's growing collection of modern and contemporary art. The collection includes works on paper, primarily drawings and photographs, as well as paintings, sculpture, and media arts. The Contemporary Collection houses works from artists, including many active in Southern California from 1960 to the present. Hammer Contemporary Collection works are often acquired in tandem with exhibitions presented at the museum, including the Hammer Projects series focusing on the work of emerging artists.\n\nThe 2009 exhibition Second Nature: The Valentine-Adelson Collection<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2009/second-nature-the-valentine-adelson-collection-at-the-hammer/ |title=Second Nature: The Valentine-Adelson Collection at the Hammer |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> at the Hammer exhibited selections from Dean Valentine and Amy Adelson's gift to the Hammer Contemporary Collection. The gift of fifty sculptures by 29 Los Angeles artists represents a significant milestone in the Hammer's commitment to collecting the works of Southern California artists.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2005/thing/ |title=Thing: New Sculpture from Los Angeles |date=2005 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the Hammer showcased selections from the Susan and Larry Marx Collection.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2012/intimate-immensity-the-susan-and-larry-marx-collection/ |title=Susan and Larry Marx Collection |date=2012 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> The exhibition was made possible by a substantial gift from longtime museum supporters Susan and Larry Marx and includes more than 150 paintings, sculptures, and works on paper by over 100 international artists from the post-World War II period. The collection includes examples of Abstract Expressionism on canvas and paper by the American artists [[Jackson Pollock]], [[Willem de Kooning]], and Philip Guston as well as works by contemporary artists including Mark Bradford, Rachel Whiteread, Mary Heilmann, and Mark Grotjahn among others.\n\nHighlights from the contemporary collection include: ''The Battle of Atlanta: Being the Narrative of a Negress in the Flames of Desire - A Reconstruction'' (1995) by Kara Walker, Untitled (2007) by [[Mark Bradford]], Migration (2008) by [[Doug Aitken]], Untitled #5 (2010) by [[Lari Pittman]], Mirage (2011) by Katie Grinnan, Ruby I (2012) by Mary Weatherford, Mimus Act I (2012) by [[Mary Kelly (artist)|Mary Kelly]].\n\nNotable recent acquisitions to the Hammer Contemporary Collection include [[Suzanne Lacy]]'s ''Three Weeks in May'' (1977), as well as major works by [[Lisa Anne Auerbach]], [[Fiona Connor]], Bruce Connor, Jeremy Deller, [[Jessica Jackson Hutchins]], Friedrich Kunath, [[Tala Madani]], Robert Overby, [[Martha Rosler]], [[Sterling Ruby]], [[Allen Ruppersberg]], Barbara T. Smith, William Leavitt, and Eric Wesley.\n\n===UCLA Grunwald Center for the Graphic Arts at the Hammer Museum===\n[[File:Pablo Picasso, 1904, Le repas frugal (The Frugal Repast), etching, Hammer Museum, University of California.jpg|thumb|Pablo Picasso, 1904, ''Le repas frugal'' (''The Frugal Repast''). Printed in 1913. Etching. Plate: 46.7 x 36 cm; Sheet: 65.4 x 47.6 cm]]\nThe UCLA Grunwald Center for the Graphic Arts is one of the most important and comprehensive collections of works on paper in the country. Housed at the Hammer Museum, the center was established in 1956 after a gift from Fred Grunwald and today houses over 40,000 prints, drawings, photographs, and artists' books.<ref name=\"grunwald-center\"/> The collection includes works dating from the Renaissance to the present, including European old master prints and drawings, Japanese ukiyo-e woodblock prints, and a collection of contemporary photography initiated by UCLA photographer Robert Heinecken (1931\u20132006).<ref>{{cite book |title=Catalog of the UCLA Collection of Contemporary American Photographs |last1=Nordland |first1=Gerald |last2=Heinecken |first2=Robert |date=1976 |location=Los Angeles |publisher=Anderson, Ritchie and Simon}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988 the Grunwald Center received a bequest of over 850 landscape drawings and prints from the collection of Los Angeles-based architect Rudolf L. Baumfeld. The Baumfeld Collection includes important examples of European landscapes from the 16th to 20th-centuries and includes pure landscapes, as well as views of architectural ruins and urban scenes.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Rudolf L. Baumfeld Collection of Landscape Drawings & Prints |date=1989 |location=Los Angeles |publisher=The Center}}</ref> The Eunice and Hal David Collection, bequeathed to the Grunwald Center by lyricist Hal David and his wife Eunice,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2003/the-eunice-and-hal-david-collection/ |title=The Eunice and Hal David Collection |date=2003 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref> is a collection of 19th and 20th-century drawings by European and American artists. Selections from the collection were exhibited at the Hammer in 2003.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Eunice and Hal David Collection of Nineteenth and Twentieth-Century Works on Paper |last1=Burlingham |first1=Cynthia |last2=Hendrix |first2=Lee |last3=Brodie |first3=Judith |date=2003 |location=Los Angeles |publisher=UCLA Grunwald Center for the Graphic Arts, UCLA Hammer Museum}}</ref> The 2014 exhibition<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2014/tea-and-morphine-women-in-paris-1880-to-1914/ |title=Tea and Morphine: Women in Paris, 1880 to 1914 |date=2014 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref> showcased works from the Elisabeth Dean Collection of 19th and 20th-century works on paper. The collection of approximately 900 prints and illustrated books is among one of the most significant gifts received by the Grunwald Center in recent years.\n\nThe Grunwald Center is also home to several important collections of Los Angeles-based contemporary artists.<ref>{{cite book |title=Grunwald Center Studies |date=1980 |location=Los Angeles |publisher=Grunwald Center for the Graphic Arts}}</ref> The Grunwald Center's collection features over 1,000 works by Sister [[Corita Kent]], an influential pop printmaker and social justice activist, including rare preparatory studies and sketchbooks.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-11-07/entertainment/ca-923_1_corita-kent |title=Documentary Remembers Nun and Artist Corita Kent |first=Shauna |last=Snow |date=November 7, 1989 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307232424/http://articles.latimes.com/1989-11-07/entertainment/ca-923_1_corita-kent |archive-date=March 7, 2016}}</ref> Additionally, the Grunwald maintains an archive of the first twenty years of [[June Wayne]]'s influential Tamarind Lithography Workshop, offering a rare overview of contemporary print-making in Los Angeles. Jointly acquired by the Grunwald and the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]], the Grunwald Center maintains a complete archive of prints by Los Angeles publisher Edition Jacob Samuel which documents the activity of master intaglio print-maker Jacob Samuel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/blog/2010/04/hammer-lacma-jointly-acquire-archive-of-edition-jacob-samuel/ |title=Hammer & LACMA Jointly Acquire Archive of Edition Jacob Samuel |date=April 27, 2010 |website=Hammer Museum |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref> Highlights from the archive were exhibited in the 2010 exhibition Outside the Box: Edition Jacob Samuel, 1988-2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2010/outside-the-box/ |title=Outside the Box |date=2010 |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA research and education resource, the Grunwald Center study room is available by appointment to faculty, students, and members of the public.\n\nHighlights from the Grunwald's collection include: ''Melencolia I'' (1514) by [[Albrecht D\u00fcrer]], ''Christ Preaching'' (1652) by [[Rembrandt van Rijn]], ''Maple trees at Mama, Tekona Shrine and linked Bridge'' (1857) by [[Utagawa Hiroshige]], ''Les Grands Baigneurs'' (1896) by [[Paul C\u00e9zanne]], ''Le Repas Frugal'' (1904) by [[Pablo Picasso]], and ''Entropia (review)'' (2004), by [[Julie Mehretu]].\n\n===Franklin D. Murphy Sculpture Garden===\nThe [[Franklin D. Murphy Sculpture Garden]] at [[UCLA]] was inaugurated in 1967 and dedicated to the [[Franklin David Murphy|eponymous chancellor]] of the university. Designed by famed landscape architect Ralph Cornell, the garden houses over 70 works of modern and contemporary sculpture in a five-acre, park-like setting. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://tclf.org/landscapes/franklin-d-murphy-sculpture-garden |title=Franklin D. Murphy Sculpture Garden |website=The Cultural Landscape Foundation |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tclf.org/news/features/illuminating-los-angeles-design-legacy-ralph-cornell |title=Illuminating the Los Angeles Design Legacy of Ralph Cornell |date=November 17, 2014 |website=The Cultural Landscape Foundation |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://cglhs.org/public-landscapes-ralph-d-cornell/ |title=The Public Landscapes of Ralph D. Cornell |date=November 9, 2014 |website=California Garden Landscape History Society |accessdate=March 6, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617043001/http://cglhs.org/public-landscapes-ralph-d-cornell/ |archive-date=June 17, 2015}}</ref> Group tours of the garden can be scheduled through the Hammer's online request form.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/visit/tours/adult-college-senior-tour-request/ |title=Adult, College & Senior Tour Request |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307153052/http://hammer.ucla.edu/visit/tours/adult-college-senior-tour-request/ |archive-date=March 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe 72 object collection comprises works by Deborah Butterfield, [[Alexander Calder]], [[Henri Matisse]], [[Joan Mir\u00f3]], [[Henry Moore]], [[Isamu Noguchi]], [[Auguste Rodin]], and [[David Smith (sculptor)|David Smith]]. A fully illustrated catalogue, including scholarly entries for each artist, was published by in 2007 by the Hammer Museum.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Franklin D. Murphy Sculpture Garden at UCLA |last=Burlingham |first=Cynthia |date=2007 |location=Los Angeles |publisher=Hammer Museum |isbn=978-0-94373-933-5}}</ref>\n\n===Armand Hammer Collection===\nThe Armand Hammer Collection<ref name=\"armand-hammer\"/> is a small selection of European and American paintings, drawings, and prints that formed the original impetus for the foundation of the Hammer Museum. [[Armand Hammer]], the founder and namesake of the museum, assembled and refined the collection through decades of involvement in the art market, both as a collector in his own right and as a co-founder of Hammer Galleries in New York City.<ref>{{cite book |title=Hammer |last1=Hammer |first1=Armand |last2=Lyndon |first2=Neil |author-link2=Neil Lyndon|date=1987 |location=New York |publisher=Putnam |isbn=978-0-39951-441-8 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/hammerar00hamm }}</ref> The focus of the collection is primarily 19th century and early-20th century French impressionist and post-impressionist paintings, though the collection itself spans the 16th through the 20th century.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Armand Hammer Collection: Five Centuries of Masterpieces |last1=Walker |first1=John |last2=Cain |first2=James Frederick |date=1980 |location=New York |publisher=Abrams |isbn=978-0-81091-069-0}}</ref>\n\nSelections from the collection are on permanent display in the Hammer Museum's third floor galleries, offering patrons a glimpse into some of the most historically relevant movements in Western art. With eminent examples of realism, orientalism, impressionism, and post-impressionism, the collection offers a unique overview of French and American art in the 19th century. Highlights of the collection include: ''Juno'' (ca. 1665-1668) by [[Rembrandt van Rijn]], ''The Education of the Virgin'' (1748-1752) by [[Jean-Honor\u00e9 Fragonard]], ''El Pelele'' (ca. 1791) by [[Francisco Goya]], ''[[Salome Dancing before Herod]]'' (1876) by [[Gustave Moreau]], ''Dr. Pozzi at Home'' (1881) by [[John Singer Sargent]], ''Bonjour Monsieur Gauguin'' (1889) by [[Paul Gauguin]], and ''Hospital at Saint-Remy'' (1889) by [[Vincent van Gogh]].\n\n===Daumier and Contemporaries Collection===\n[[File:Hospital at Saint Remy.jpg|thumb|Vincent van Gogh. ''Hospital at Saint-R\u00e9my'', 1889. Oil on canvas. 36 5/16 x 28 7/8 in. (92.2 x 73.4 cm). The Armand Hammer Collection, Gift of the Armand Hammer Foundation. Hammer Museum, Los Angeles.]]\n\nThe Honor\u00e9 Daumier and Contemporaries Collection<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/collections/armand-hammer-daumier-and-contemporaries-collection/ |title=Honor\u00e9 Daumier and Contemporaries Collection |website=Hammer Museum |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> at the Hammer Museum is one of the most important collections of Daumier works outside France. Housing over 7,500 works of art by the French satirist [[Honor\u00e9 Daumier]] (1808-1879) and other contemporary [[List of caricaturists|caricaturists]], it is the largest of its kind outside of Paris. Daumier, whose life and career spanned the 19th century, was a brilliant [[satire|satirist]] whose works offered incisive comment on the hypocrisies of bourgeois life in the French capital.<ref>{{cite book |title=Honor\u00e9 Daumier 1808-1879: The Armand Hammer Daumier Collection |date=1981 |location=Los Angeles |publisher=Armand Hammer Foundation}}</ref> Daumier was an extremely prolific artist whose work spans multiple media, and as such the collection includes paintings, drawings, lithographs, and a series of bronze portrait busts; all keen examples of Daumier's mordant wit and acerbic attitude towards contemporary politics. Selections from the Daumier and Contemporaries collection are on rotating display alongside works from the Armand Hammer Collection.\n\nHighlights from the Daumier and Contemporaries Collection include Daumier's ''Le pass\u00e9 - Le present - L'avenir'' (1834), ''Un Avocat Plaidant,'' (ca. 1845) ''Nadar \u00e9levant la Photographie \u00e1 la hauteur de l'Art'' (1862), and ''Don Quixote et Sancho Panza'' (1866-1868).\n\n==Programs==\nA diverse range of free public programs are presented at the Hammer Museum six evenings a week throughout the year, including lectures, readings, symposia, film screenings, musical performances, and other events. The [[Billy Wilder]] Theater opened at the Hammer Museum in late 2006, after a $5 million gift from Audrey L. Wilder, the widow of Billy Wilder, enabled the museum to resume building a 300-seat theater left unfinished at Armand Hammer's death.<ref name=\"NYT-Sheets\"/> Its 2006 opening coincided with the centennial of Wilder's birth. The venue currently houses the [[UCLA Film and Television Archive]]'s well-known [[cinematheque]] as well as the Hammer's 300 public programs a year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artinfo.com/galleryguide/20125/6664/about/hammer-museum-los-angeles/ |title=Hammer Museum: About |website=[[Artinfo]] |accessdate=July 11, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706191525/http://www.artinfo.com/galleryguide/20125/6664/about/hammer-museum-los-angeles/ |archivedate=July 6, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nPopular series include a weekly meditation program, the Libros Schmibros book club, and the Hammer Conversations which place major cultural, political, and intellectual leaders in dialog with one another. Past Hammer Conversations participants include the writers [[Joan Didion]], [[Jonathan Lethem]], and [[George Saunders]], the filmmakers [[Atom Egoyan]] and [[Miranda July]], journalist [[Naomi Klein]], comedians [[Jeff Garlin]] and [[Patton Oswalt]], playwright and screenwriter [[David Mamet]], magician [[Ricky Jay]], artists [[Betye Saar]] and [[Sam Durant]], actors [[Leonard Nimoy]] and [[Zachary Quinto]], and many others.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailybruin.com/index.php/blog/spotlight/2011/01/hammer_conversations_program_/ |title=Hammer Conversations program offers insight into philosophies of political artists Tom Morello and Sam Durant |last=Somasundaram |first=Niran |date=January 13, 2011 |newspaper=[[Daily Bruin]] |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref> A striking example of the timeliness and popularity of these events occurred in March 2003, when 2,000 people gathered at the Hammer Museum to hear [[Gore Vidal]] speak about the Iraq war the night before bombing began. Since 2010, the Hammer has partnered with the radio station [[KCRW]] to host an annual outdoor summer concert series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.kcrw.com/musicnews/2010/05/kcrw-hammer-museum-present-the-also-i-like-to-rock-free-concert-series-this-july/ |title=KCRW & Hammer Museum Present the \"Also I Like to Rock\" Free Concert Series This July! |last=Reynolds |first=Rachel |date=May 12, 2010 |website=[[KCRW]] Music Blog |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the past, the Hammer traditionally focused on university-level education programs because of its affiliation with UCLA.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/16/entertainment/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-anthony-pritzker-20130915 |title=Hammer Museum gets $2-million gift from Anthony Pritzker |last=Ng |first=David |date=September 16, 2013 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113053702/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/16/entertainment/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-anthony-pritzker-20130915 |archive-date=January 13, 2016}}</ref> Since 2009, the Hammer has been annually inviting an accomplished group of Los Angeles artists to lead workshops based on their working processes on the occasion of the Kids' Art Museum Project (K.A.M.P). Unlike other family events, K.A.M.P. provides access and experiences for children and their families with renowned Los Angeles artists, many of whom have been the subject of exhibitions at the Hammer Museum. Past participating artists include [[Edgar Arceneaux]], [[Mark Grotjahn]], [[Catherine Opie]], [[Jorge Pardo (artist)|Jorge Pardo]], and [[Jonas Wood]]. Each year the event features a series of celebrities reading from their favorite children's books in the museum's galleries, such as [[Will Ferrell]], [[Jason Bateman]], [[Hilary Swank]], [[Jodie Foster]] and [[Zoe Saldana]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/julie-bowen-jodie-foster-join-500015 |title=Julie Bowen, Jodie Foster Join Hammer Museum's K.A.M.P. Event |last=Wyrick |first=Christopher |date=May 6, 2013 |newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Hammer Museum Westwood June 2012.jpg|thumb|left|Hammer Museum building in Westwood, Los Angeles]]\nThe museum was founded by [[Armand Hammer]], the late CEO of the [[Occidental Petroleum|Occidental Petroleum Corporation]], as a venue to exhibit his extensive art collection, at the time valued at $250 million.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20098584,00.html |title=Thanks to Medicis Like Norton Simon and Armand Hammer, a Gilded Dilly of An Art Scene Flowers in L.A. |last1=Small |first1=Michael |last2=Savaiano |first2=Jacqueline |date=March 28, 1988 |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303221351/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20098584,00.html |archive-date=March 3, 2016}}</ref> A [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]] board member for nearly 20 years, Hammer withdrew from a non-binding agreement to transfer his paintings to LACMA after disagreements regarding how his collection would be displayed. Shortly thereafter, on January 21, 1988, Hammer announced plans to build his own museum on the site of a Westwood parking garage adjacent to the Occidental headquarters.<ref name=\"LAT-Battle\">{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-05-22/magazine/tm-4568_1_armand-hammer-collection |title=Battle for the Masterpieces : The Armand Hammer-County Museum Deal: A Saga of Art, Power and Big Misunderstandings |first=Robert A. |last=Jones |date=May 22, 1988 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111001914/http://articles.latimes.com/1988-05-22/magazine/tm-4568_1_armand-hammer-collection |archive-date=January 11, 2011}}</ref> Community leaders who hailed the plan as a positive turning point in the neighborhood's development were soon overshadowed by complaints from Occidental shareholders who sued the company over the museum's escalating construction costs, which were capped by a federal judge at $60 million.<ref name=\"LAT-Battle\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-01-28/news/we-39037_1_armand-hammer-museum |title=Westwood Village Pins Hopes for Renaissance on Hammer Museum |first=Philipp |last=Gollner |date=January 28, 1988 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305212715/http://articles.latimes.com/1988-01-28/news/we-39037_1_armand-hammer-museum |archive-date=March 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-02-21/entertainment/ca-1119_1_armand-hammer-museum |title=Armand Hammer Museum: Who Paid for What? : Art: Internal Occidental documents indicate that officials may have transferred millions of dollars to other corporate accounts to meet budget goal |first=Allan |last=Parachini |date=February 21, 1990 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106031637/http://articles.latimes.com/1990-02-21/entertainment/ca-1119_1_armand-hammer-museum |archive-date=January 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-02-22/entertainment/ca-1803_1_hammer-museum |title=Dissident Shareholder Claims Oxy Falsified Museum Books |first=Allan |last=Parachini |date=February 22, 1990 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180515094317/http://articles.latimes.com/1990-02-22/entertainment/ca-1803_1_hammer-museum |archive-date=May 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDesigned by Edward Larrabee Barnes, the New York-based architect responsible for the Dallas Museum of Art and the Walker Art Center, the building housing the museum was conceived as a Renaissance palazzo with galleries centered around a tranquil, interior courtyard and a relatively austere exterior profile.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-01-13/realestate/re-94_1_hammer-museum |title=Critique : Hammer's Modest Museum |first=Leon |last=Whiteson |date=January 13, 1991 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170409021604/http://articles.latimes.com/1991-01-13/realestate/re-94_1_hammer-museum |archive-date=April 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, architect [[Michael Maltzan]] designed the [[Billy Wilder]] Theater and the museum's caf\u00e9. Michael Maltzan Architecture also designed the John V. Tunney Bridge, which opened in February 2015. The pedestrian bridge, named in honor of [[John V. Tunney]], longtime Chairman of the Board of Directors of the Hammer Museum, connects the upper level galleries over the Hammer Courtyard.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-bridge-michael-maltzan-20141119-story.html |title=Courtyard bridge by Michael Maltzan to open at Hammer in February |first=Jessica |last=Gelt |date=November 19, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHammer died less than a month after his namesake museum opened to the public in November 1990, leaving the fledgling institution mired in litigation over its financing and prompting new legal battles regarding the disposition of Hammer's estate. While the museum's operating budget was provided by a $36 million annuity purchased by [[Occidental Petroleum]], questions remained regarding the future of the museum's collections and the role that the Hammer family would play in its administration.<ref name=\"LAT-Litigation\"/> In 1994, the Regents of the University of California entered into a 99-year operating agreement with the Armand Hammer Foundation to assume management of the museum, which afforded the fledgling institution a measure of stability. At that point the exhibition programs of the Wight Art Gallery, UCLA's existing museum, and the Grunwald Center for the Graphic Arts, the university's print collection, were moved to the Hammer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arts.ucla.edu/press/pdf/UCLAArtsHistory.pdf |title=UCLA Arts History |date=July 23, 2008 |website=UCLA School of the Arts & Architecture |accessdate=March 6, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123033139/https://www.arts.ucla.edu/press/pdf/UCLAArtsHistory.pdf/ |archive-date=January 23, 2015}}</ref> A 2007 a settlement between the UC Regents and the Hammer Foundation formally ended long-simmering disputes over the Hammer collection's ownership and established new guidelines for its display that allowed the museum more space for exhibitions and a growing contemporary collection.<ref name=\"LAT-Divided\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2007/jan/19/entertainment/et-hammer19 |title=Hammer divided yet strong |first=Suzanne |last=Muchnic |authorlink=Suzanne Muchnic |date=January 19, 2007 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 19, 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306032652/http://articles.latimes.com/2007/jan/19/entertainment/et-hammer19 |archive-date=March 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDespite the institutional hurdles that earned it the nickname \"America's vainest museum\" at its inception, the Hammer is now widely acknowledged as \"a hot spot for contemporary art and ideas and a venue for serious exploration of overlooked historical subjects.\" Under current leadership, the Hammer's budget has grown from $5 million to roughly $20 million annually, with a full-time staff of over 100.<ref name=\"LAT-Striking\">{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-ca-philbin18-2009oct18-story.html |title=The Hammer Museum's striking rise |first=Suzanne |last=Muchnic |date=October 18, 2009 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324115719/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-ca-philbin18-2009oct18-story.html |archive-date=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-Life-Support\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/23/arts/design/hurdles-grow-at-the-museum-of-contemporary-art-los-angeles.html |title=A Los Angeles Museum on Life-Support |first=Roberta |last=Smith |date=July 22, 2012 |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, amidst the [[Coronavirus pandemic]], the museum was temporary closed and laid off its 150 part-time student employees.<ref name=\"LAT-Hammer-Covid\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/story/2020-03-25/hammer-museum-layoffs-student-employees |title=Hammer Museum lays off 150 student employees |first=Deborah |last=Vankin |date=March 25, 2020 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Management==\n\n===Directors===\nIn 1994, Henry Hopkins, then director of the Wight gallery and professor in the Department of Art at UCLA, became director of the Museum. He served in that position until his retirement in 1998.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/arts/la-me-henry-hopkins29-2009sep29,0,6304306.story |title=Henry T. Hopkins dies at 81; painter and museum director had formative role in L.A. art scene |last=Muchnic |first=Suzanne |date=September 28, 2009 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091026164048/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/arts/la-me-henry-hopkins29-2009sep29,0,6304306.story |archive-date=October 26, 2009}}</ref> In 1999 [[Ann Philbin]], previously director of [[The Drawing Center]] in New York, was named director and still serves as director today.\n\n===Board of Directors and Board of Overseers===\n\nThe Hammer Museum was founded by Dr. Armand Hammer. [[Michael Armand Hammer]] is Chairman Emeritus, and [[Armie Hammer]] and Viktor Armand Hammer are Honorary Directors. Michael Rubel serves as President, Nelson C. Rising serves as Vice President, and Steven A. Olsen serves as Treasurer. Under Chair [[Marcy Carsey]], the Hammer's Board of Directors also includes Heather R. Axe, Ren\u00e9e Becnel, [[Gene Block]], Lloyd E. Cotsen, [[Eric Esrailian]], Erika J. Glazer, Manuela Herzer, Larry Marx, [[Anthony Pritzker]], Lee Ramer, Kevin L. Ratner, Chip Rosenbloom, Steven P. Song, John V. Tunney, [[Kevin Wall]], John Walsh, and Christopher A. Waterman.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/about-us/museum-boards/ |title=Boards and Governance |website=Hammer Museum |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref> Members of the Board of Overseers include artists [[Barbara Kruger]] and [[Lari Pittman]]. The museum does not disclose its annual board membership dues.\n\n===Funding===\nIn 1994, the [[Regents of the University of California]] entered into a 99-year operating agreement with the Armand Hammer Foundation<ref name=\"LAT-Divided\"/> and assumed management of the Hammer Museum, with the foundation retaining some control, including a \"reversionary clause,\"<ref name=\"LAT-Striking\"/> granting the foundation rights to reclaim the art collection and some of the endowment funds. The museum had long desired to eliminate these clauses. Operating money came from a bond portfolio, UCLA's existing art budgets, private donations, and revenue from the museum.<ref name=\"LAT-Striking\"/> In 2009, the museum operates on an annual operating budget of $14 million, 10% to 12% of which comes from the university. By the fiscal year 2011, its budget of $16 million surpassed that of the much larger [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"NYT-Life-Support\"/>\n\t\nOn January 19, 2007 the Hammer Museum and the Armand Hammer Foundation agreed to dissolve their relationship, dividing the remaining 195 objects which founded the museum; the foundation retaining 92 paintings valued at $55 million, while the museum retaining 103 objects, valued at $250 million. By 2020, the museum will use its bond portfolio, valued at about $55 million, to purchase the building that houses the museum and Occidental's former headquarters.<ref name=\"LAT-Striking\"/>\n\nIn addition, the Hammer Museum's annual Gala in the Garden serves as a fundraiser for the museum. The 2019 edition raised $2.7 million.<ref>Jori Finkel (October 15, 2019), [https://www.theartnewspaper.com/blog/i-can-divide-my-life-into-before-and-after-judy-chicago-gloria-steinem-reveals-how-the-artist-changed-her-thoughts-about-art-at-hammer-museum-gala \u2018I can divide my life into before and after Judy Chicago\u2019: Gloria Steinem reveals how the artist changed her thoughts about art at Hammer Museum gala] ''[[The Art Newspaper]]''.</ref> Recent museum honorees include [[Robert Gober]], [[Tony Kushner]], [[Barbara Kruger]] and [[Cindy Sherman]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-diane-keaton-paul-mccarthy-hammer-museum-20150520-story.html |title=Diane Keaton, Paul McCarthy to be honored at Hammer Museum |last=Ng |first=David |date=May 20, 2015 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Attendance===\nAt the Hammer Museum, 2010 attendance was an estimated 175,000, up from 150,000 in 2009.<ref name=\"JoriFinkel-2011\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/mar/30/entertainment/la-et-museum-attendance-2-20110329/2 |title=Attendance at L.A. museums lags behind |last=Finkel |first=Jori |date=March 30, 2011 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=6 March 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106080240/http://articles.latimes.com/2011/mar/30/entertainment/la-et-museum-attendance-2-20110329/2 |archive-date=November 6, 2012}}</ref> As of 2013, annual attendance for permanent collection, special exhibitions and programs stands at about 200,000.<ref name=\"knight-hammer\"/> The museum does not provide exact figures as it does not have a computerized ticketing system.<ref name=\"JoriFinkel-2011\"/> According to the museum's director Ann Philbin, the museum has \"defined our primary audience as artists\".<ref name=\"LATM-tastemaker\"/> Visitor numbers are also not limited to the Hammer's own box office but might also include people around the world who log on to the museum's Web site to view podcasts of public programs, or visit travelling exhibitions which the Hammer organized.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/08/arts/design/08museum.html |title=Sketching a Future for Brooklyn Museum |last=Pogrebin |first=Robin |date=August 5, 2010 |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Deaccessioning===\nIn 1994, the Hammer Museum made headlines by selling [[Leonardo da Vinci|Leonardo da Vinci's]] [[Codex Leicester]] to [[Microsoft]] founder [[Bill Gates]] for $30.8 million. The Codex Leicester was one of Dr. Hammer's proudest acquisitions, purchased in 1980 for $5.12 million, and one which he unsuccessfully tried to rename the ''Codex Hammer''.<ref name=\"Time1991\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,972206,00.html |title=America's Vainest Museum |last=Hughes |first=Robert |author-link=Robert Hughes (critic) |date=January 28, 1991 |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]] |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> Most museums have [[Collection (museum)|collection]] guidelines for deaccessing art, which require the revenue from sales to be used for future acquisitions. The Hammer Museum alternatively sold the 72-page scientific notebook to fund the museum's exhibitions and programs.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite news |url=http://www.calendarlive.com/printedition/calendar/cl-et-hammer15jan15,0,5571996.story?coll=cl-calendar |first1=Christopher |last1=Reynolds |first2=Hugh |last2=Hart |title=The Da Vinci codex versus the museum code |date=January 15, 2007 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=January 15, 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070117115447/http://www.calendarlive.com/printedition/calendar/cl-et-hammer15jan15,0,5571996.story?coll=cl-calendar |archive-date=January 17, 2007}}\n* {{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2007/jan/22/entertainment/et-hammer22 |title=The Hammer cleanup |first=Christopher |last=Knight |authorlink=Christopher Knight (art critic) |date=January 22, 2007 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 22, 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140515201824/http://articles.latimes.com/2007/jan/22/entertainment/et-hammer22 |archive-date=May 15, 2014}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Hammer Museum}}\n*{{official website|http://www.hammer.ucla.edu/}}\n\n{{UCLA}}\n{{Westwood, Los Angeles}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hammer Museum| ]]\n[[Category:Art museums and galleries in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:University museums in California]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:1990 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 1990]]\n[[Category:Art in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Westwood, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Wilshire Boulevard]]\n[[Category:Edward Larrabee Barnes buildings]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reword - you can't be \"among one\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hammer_Museum"}
{"title_page": "USS Thresher (SSN-593)", "text_new": "{{other ships|USS Thresher}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=[[File:USS Thresher;0859306.jpg|300px|USS Thresher (SSN-593) underway, 30 April 1961]]\n|Ship caption=USS ''Thresher'' (SSN-593) underway, 30 April 1961\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1963}}\n|Ship name=''Thresher''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship ordered=15 January 1958\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder=[[Portsmouth Naval Shipyard]]\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=28 May 1958\n|Ship launched=9 July 1960\n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=3 August 1961\n|Ship recommissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship maiden voyage=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship motto=''Vis Tacita'' (Silent Strength)\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship fate=Lost with all hands during deep diving tests, 10 April 1963; 129 died.\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{Sclass-|Thresher|submarine}}\n|Ship displacement={{convert|3540|ST|t|abbr=on}} light, {{convert|3770|ST|t|abbr=on}} submerged\n|Ship length={{convert|279|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|32|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draft={{convert|26|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion=1 Westinghouse [[S5W reactor|S5W PWR]], Westinghouse Geared Turbines {{convert|15,000|shp|MW|abbr=on}}\n|Ship speed={{convert|33|kn}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship test depth=\n|Ship boats=\n|Ship capacity=\n|Ship troops=\n|Ship complement=16 officers, 96 men\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=4 \u00d7 {{convert|21|in|mm|abbr=on}} [[torpedo tube]]s amidships\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\nThe second '''USS ''Thresher'' (SSN-593)''' was the [[lead boat]] of [[Permit-class submarine|her class]] of nuclear-powered attack [[submarine]]s in the [[United States Navy]]. She was the U.S. Navy's [[USS Thresher (SS-200)|second submarine]] to be named after the [[thresher shark]].\n\nOn 10 April 1963, ''Thresher'' sank during deep-diving tests about {{convert|220|mi|km|abbr=on|order=flip}} east of Boston, Massachusetts, killing all 129 crew and shipyard personnel aboard. It is the second-deadliest submarine incident on record, after the loss of the French submarine [[French submarine Surcouf|''Surcouf'']], in which 130 crew died.<ref name=\"deadliest1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.naval-technology.com/features/featureperil-in-the-depths-the-worlds-worst-submarine-disasters-4191027/ |last=Duddu|first=Praveen|title=Peril in the depths \u2013 the world's worst submarine disasters |website=Navaltechnology.com |date= 6 March 2014 |accessdate=7 August 2018 }}</ref><ref name=Polmar /> Her loss was a watershed for the U.S. Navy, leading to the implementation of a rigorous submarine safety program known as [[SUBSAFE]]. The first [[List of sunken nuclear submarines|nuclear submarine lost at sea]], ''Thresher'' was also the third of four submarine losses that killed over 100 aboard; the others being the [[USS Argonaut (SM-1)|Argonaut]], lost with 102 aboard in World War II, the Surcouf, and the ''[[Kursk submarine disaster|Kursk]]'', which sank with 118 aboard in 2000.\n\n==Significance of design and loss==\nCreated to find and destroy [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] submarines, ''Thresher'' was the fastest and quietest submarine of the day, matching the smaller, contemporary {{sclass-|Skipjack|submarine|4}}. She also had the most advanced weapons system, including launchers for the U.S. Navy's newest [[anti-submarine missile]], the [[UUM-44 SUBROC|SUBROC]], as well as passive and active sonar that could detect vessels at unprecedented range. Shortly after her loss, the [[COMSUBLANT#Officers serving as COMSUBLANT|Commander of Submarine Force Atlantic]] wrote in the March 1964 issue of the [[U.S. Naval Institute]]'s monthly journal ''Proceedings'' that \"the Navy had depended upon this performance to the extent that it had asked for and received authority to build 14 of these ships, as well as an additional 11 submarines with very much the same characteristics. This was the first time since World War II that we had considered our design sufficiently advanced to embark upon construction of a large class of general-purpose attack submarines.\"{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nFollowing Navy tradition, this class of subs was originally named ''Thresher'' after the lead boat.  When ''Thresher'' was struck from the [[Naval Vessel Register]] on 16 April 1963, the class name was changed to that of the second boat, {{USS|Permit|SSN-594|2}}, and ''Thresher'' is now officially referred to as a [[Permit-class submarine|''Permit''-class submarine]]. Having been \"lost at sea\", ''Thresher'' was not decommissioned by the U.S. Navy and remains on \"Eternal Patrol\".{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n==Early career==\n[[File:USS Thresher (SSN-593) bow.jpg|thumb|left|''Thresher'' at sea on 24 July 1961]]\nThe contract to build ''Thresher'' was awarded to [[Portsmouth Naval Shipyard]] on 15 January 1958, and her [[keel]] was laid on 28 May 1958. She was [[ship naming and launching|launched]] on 9 July 1960, was sponsored by Mrs. Mary B. Warder<ref name=Polmar>{{cite book |title=The Death of the USS Thresher: The Story Behind History's Deadliest Submarine Disaster |author=Polmar, Norman |authorlink=Norman Polmar |isbn=978-1592283927}}</ref> (wife of [[World War II]] skipper Frederick B. Warder), and was [[ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 3 August 1961, [[Commander (United States)|Commander]] Dean L. Axene commanding.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n''Thresher'' conducted lengthy sea trials in the western Atlantic and [[Caribbean Sea]] areas in 1961\u20131962. These tests allowed a thorough evaluation of her many new and complex technological features and weapons. She took part in Nuclear Submarine Exercise (NUSUBEX) 3\u201361 off the northeastern coast of the United States from 18\u201324 September 1961.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nOn 18 October 1961, ''Thresher,'' in company with the diesel-electric submarine {{USS|Cavalla|SS-244|2}}, headed south on a 3-week test and training cruise to [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], arriving 2 November. Following customary procedure while in port, her reactor was shut down. Since no shore power connection was available in San Juan, the ship's backup [[diesel generator]] was used to carry the [[Hotel electric power|\"hotel\" electrical loads]]. Several hours later, the backup generator broke down and the electrical load was transferred to the ship's battery.  As most of the battery power was needed to keep vital systems operating and to restart the reactor, lighting and air conditioning were shut down. Without air conditioning, temperature and humidity in the submarine rose, reaching {{convert|60|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|abbr=on}} after about 10 hours. The crew attempted to repair the diesel generator (four men would receive [[Commendation Medal|Navy commendation medals]] for their work that night). After it became apparent that the generator could not be fixed before the battery was depleted, the crew tried to restart the reactor, but the remaining battery charge was insufficient. The captain, returning to the ship from a shore function, arrived just after the battery ran down. The crew eventually borrowed cables from another ship in the harbor and connected them to the adjacent ''Cavalla'', which started her diesels and provided enough power to allow ''Thresher'' to restart her reactor.<ref>Polmar, pp. 13\u201317</ref>\n\n''Thresher'' conducted further trials and fired test [[torpedo]]es before returning to Portsmouth on 29 November 1961. The boat remained in port through the end of the year, and spent the first two months of 1962 evaluating her [[sonar]] and SUBROC systems. In March, she participated in NUSUBEX 2\u201362 (an exercise designed to improve the tactical capabilities of nuclear submarines) and in [[anti-submarine warfare]] training with Task Group ALPHA.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nOff [[Charleston, South Carolina]], ''Thresher'' undertook operations supporting development of the [[UUM-44 SUBROC|SUBROC anti-submarine missile]].  She returned briefly to [[New England]] waters, after which she proceeded to Florida for more SUBROC tests. While moored at [[Port Canaveral, Florida]], the submarine was accidentally struck by a tug, which damaged one of her [[ballast tanks]]. After repairs at [[Groton, Connecticut]], by the [[Electric Boat]] Company, ''Thresher'' went south for more tests and trials off [[Key West, Florida]], then returned northward. The submarine entered Portsmouth Shipyard on 16 July 1962 to begin a scheduled 6-month post-shakedown availability to examine systems and make repairs and corrections as necessary. As is typical with a first-of-class boat, the work took longer than expected, lasting nearly 9 months. The ship was finally recertified and undocked on 8 April 1963.<ref>[http://www.navalhistory.org/2013/04/01/uss-thresher-ssn-593-3-august-1961-10-april-1963 \"USS ''Thresher''\"], article by Vice Admiral E.W. Grenfell, ''U.S. Naval Institute Proceedings'', March 1964; accessed 6 April 2013.</ref>\n\n==Sinking==\nOn 9 April 1963, ''Thresher'', commanded by [[Lieutenant Commander]] John Wesley Harvey, got underway from Kittery, Maine at 08:00 and met with the submarine rescue ship {{USS|Skylark|ASR-20|2}} at 11:00 to begin her initial post-overhaul dive trials, in an area some {{convert|190|nmi|mi km|abbr=on|order=flip}} east of [[Cape Cod, Massachusetts]]. That afternoon ''Thresher'' conducted an initial trim dive test, surfaced, and then performed a second dive to half of test depth. She remained submerged overnight and re-established underwater communications with ''Skylark'' at 06:30 on 10 April to commence deep-dive trials. Following standard practice, ''Thresher'' slowly dove deeper as she traveled in circles under ''Skylark''&nbsp;\u2013 to remain within communications distance&nbsp;\u2013 pausing every {{convert|100|ft|abbr=on|order=flip}} of depth to check the integrity of all systems. As ''Thresher'' neared her test depth, ''Skylark'' received garbled communications over [[underwater telephone]] indicating \" ... &nbsp;minor difficulties, have positive up-angle, attempting to blow\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csp.navy.mil/othboats/593.htm |title=COMSUBPAC Web site, Submarines Lost or Damaged before and after World War II |accessdate=2 February 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060129171708/http://www.csp.navy.mil/othboats/593.htm |archivedate=29 January 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://usgovinfo.about.com/library/weekly/aa081700a.htm |title=U.S. Gov Info / Resources, US Navy's Submarine Rescue Team |accessdate=2 February 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/transcripts/2602subsecrets.html |title=NOVA Web site, transcript of \"Submarines, Secrets, and Spies\" |accessdate=2 February 2006}}</ref> and then a final even more garbled message that included the number \"900\".<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20131031061419/http://www.navsource.org/archives/08/08593b.htm Thresher (SSN 593) Loss & Inquiry], navsource.org</ref> When ''Skylark'' received no further communication, surface observers gradually realized ''Thresher'' had sunk.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nBy mid-afternoon, 15 Navy ships were en route to the search area. At 18:30, the Commander, Submarine Force Atlantic, sent word to Portsmouth Naval Shipyard to begin notifying the crew's family members, starting with Commander Harvey's wife, Irene Harvey, that ''Thresher'' was missing.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nBy morning on 11 April, all hope of finding ''Thresher'' was abandoned, and at 10:30, the Chief of Naval Operations Admiral [[George W. Anderson Jr.]], went before the press corps at [[the Pentagon]] to announce that the submarine was lost with all hands. President [[John F. Kennedy]] ordered all flags to be flown at half staff on 12\u201315 April in honor of the 129 lost submariners and shipyard personnel.<ref>{{cite web\n  |title=Executive Order 11104&nbsp;\u2013 U.S.S. Thresher\n  |author=John F. Kennedy\n  |authorlink=John F. Kennedy\n  |work=[[Executive order (United States)|Executive Order]]\n  |date=April 12, 1963 \n  |url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=59043\n}}</ref>\n\n==Search and recovery==\n[[File:Search for USS Thresher (SSN-593).jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|Search operations underway near the accident site, 15 April 1963]]\nThe Navy quickly mounted an extensive search with surface ships and support from the [[Naval Research Laboratory]] (NRL), with its deep-search capability. The laboratory's small acoustic research vessel, ''Rockville'', with a unique trainable search sonar, left on 12 April 1963 for the search area. That vessel was to be followed by other personnel with a deep-camera system. There {{ship|USS|Allegheny|ATA-179|2}}, {{ship|USNS|Mission Capistrano||2}}, and {{ship|USS|Prevail|AM-107|2}} were engaged in a close sonar search of an area {{cvt|10|nmi|km mi}} square. {{ship|RV|Atlantis II||2}}, {{ship|USNS|Robert D. Conrad|T-AGOR-3|2}}, and {{ship|USNS|James M. Gilliss|T-AGOR-4|2}} were investigating likely contacts found in the sonar search. The NRL deep-towed camera system and personnel later operated off ''James M. Gilliss'' with some success, finding debris later confirmed to be from ''Thresher''.<ref name=Bundage>{{cite report |last=Bundage |first=Walter|date=November 29, 1988 |title=NRL's Deep Sea Floor Search Era |pages=4\u201116 |url=https://archive.org/details/DTIC_ADA204011/page/n8/mode/1up/ |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> The [[bathyscaphe Trieste|bathyscaphe ''Trieste'']] was alerted on 11 April and brought from San Diego to Boston. It was deployed for two series of dives on the debris field; the first taking place from 24 to 30 June, the second from late August until early September. The equipment-handling capability of ''Gilliss'' proved inadequate, even hazardous, to handle the towed vehicle, and the entire search was paused in September.<ref name=Gennari>{{cite report |last=Gennari |first=J. J. |date=1 January 1967 |title=Center Well Installation of USNS ''Mizar'' (T-AGOR-11) |pages= |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Naval Research Laboratory  |url=https://archive.org/details/DTIC_AD0647494/mode/2up |accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=Sealift>{{cite magazine |date=July 1968 |title=Ship That Helped Locate ''Thresher'' Searching for ''Scorpion'' |magazine=Sealift Magazine |volume=18 |issue=7 |pages=3-5, 12-13 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sFsShLqioGAC&pg=PA3#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe inadequacy of the AGOR type for handling deep-towed search vehicles led to a search for a vessel of a size and configuration that could handle such equipment in a sheltered area. In late 1963 that search resulted in acquisition of {{USNS|Mizar|AGOR-11|2}}, with intent to eventually add a sheltered center well for deploying equipment.<ref name=Bundage/><ref name=Gennari/>\n\nThe 1964 search included ''Mizar'' with partial modifications but not a center well, {{ship|USS|Hoist|ARS-40|2}}, and [[Bathyscaphe Trieste II|''Trieste II'']], ''Trieste''{{'}}s successor. That submersible incorporated parts of the original bathyscaphe and was completed in early 1964. The bathyscaphe was placed on board {{USNS|Private Francis X. McGraw|T-AK-241|6}} and shipped to Boston. ''Mizar'' did have a system, Underwater Tracking Equipment (UTE), by which it could track its towed vehicle and planned to track ''Trieste''. ''Mizar'' sailed on 25 June to begin the deep search and found the wreck within two days. By July 22 most of the lost submarine had been  photographed.<ref name=Buchanan>{{cite report |last= Buchanan |first=C. L. |year=1972 |title=A Love Affair (reprinted in Bundage: NRL's Deep Sea Floor Search Era) |pages=13-15 |url=https://archive.org/details/DTIC_ADA204011/page/n16/mode/1up/ |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> In early August the entire task force returned to the area with the submersible. Its first two dives were unsuccessful, but on the third dive the UTE enabled placement of ''Trieste II'' on the wreck, at first not seeing wreckage because the bathyscaphe was sitting on it.<ref name=Buchanan/>\n\nThe shattered remains of ''Thresher''{{'}}s hull were on the sea floor, approximately {{convert|8400|ft|m|order=flip}} below the surface, in five major sections.<ref name=brand>{{cite journal |author=Brand, V |title=Submersibles&nbsp;\u2013 Manned and Unmanned. |journal=South Pacific Underwater Medicine Society Journal |volume=7 |issue=3 |year=1977 |issn=0813-1988 |oclc=16986801 |url=http://archive.rubicon-foundation.org/6154 |accessdate=10 July 2008}}</ref> Most of the debris had spread over an area of about {{convert|134000|m2|yd2}}. Major sections of ''Thresher'', including the [[sail (submarine)|sail]], sonar dome, bow section, engineering spaces section, operations spaces section, and the stern planes were found and photographed. One aspect of the search conducted that summer by ''Mizar'' involved the use of highly sensitive [[proton magnetometer]]s furnished by the Instrument Division of [[Varian Associates]] in Palo Alto, and shipped aboard ''Mizar'' before her departure from NRL in Washington. The magnetometers were used in conjunction with underwater video cameras and suspended on the same electrical line used to tow the video cameras themselves.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/our-collections/photography/numerical-list-of-images/nhhc-series/nh-series/NH-97000/NH-97555.html|title=Loss of USS Thresher|website=History.navy.mil}}</ref>\n\n''Trieste II'' was commanded by Lieutenant John B. Mooney Jr., with co-pilot Lieutenant John H. Howland and Captain Frank Andrews in an operation that recovered bits of wreckage in September 1964. The groundbreaking deep submergence operations helped in the design and construction of other deep-diving submersibles which could be used in rescuing crews and recovering objects from submarines in distress below levels reachable by conventional methods.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n==Cause==\nDeep-sea photography, recovered artifacts, and an evaluation of her design and operational history permitted a court of inquiry to conclude ''Thresher'' had probably suffered the failure of a salt-water piping system joint which relied heavily on [[silver brazing]] instead of welding.  Earlier tests using ultrasound equipment found potential problems with about 14% of the tested brazed joints,<ref>[http://www.navsea.navy.mil/NewsView.aspx?nw=NewsWires&id=224 50 Years of Steely Purpose-USS Thresher Remembered] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130626170831/http://www.navsea.navy.mil/NewsView.aspx?nw=NewsWires&id=224 |date=26 June 2013 }}. Navsea.navy.mil. 10 April 2013.</ref> most of which were determined not to pose a risk significant enough to require a repair. High-pressure water spraying from a broken pipe joint may have shorted out one of the many electrical panels, causing a shutdown (\"[[scram]]\") of the reactor, which in turn caused loss of propulsion. The inability to blow the ballast tanks was later attributed to excessive moisture in the submarine's high-pressure air flasks, moisture which froze and plugged the flasks' flowpaths while passing through the valves. This was later simulated in dock-side tests on ''Thresher''{{'}}s sister sub, {{USS|Tinosa|SSN-606|2}}. During a test to simulate blowing ballast at or near [[test depth]], ice formed on strainers installed in valves; the flow of air lasted only a few seconds.<ref>[http://www.navsource.org/archives/08/08593b.htm Thresher (SSN-593)  Loss & Inquiry] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031061419/http://www.navsource.org/archives/08/08593b.htm |date=31 October 2013 }}. Navsource.org</ref> Air dryers were later retrofitted to the high-pressure air compressors, beginning with ''Tinosa'', to permit the emergency blow system to operate properly.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nSubsequent study of [[SOSUS]] (sound surveillance system) data from the time of the incident has given rise to doubts of whether flooding preceded the reactor scram, as no impact sounds of the high pressure water in the compartments of the submarine could be detected on instrument recordings from SOSUS at the time.  Such flooding would have been a significant sonic event, and no evidence of that can be found in the recorded data.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iusscaa.org/articles/brucerule/letter_to_the_deputy_cno.htm|title=Information and Security Issues Associated with the Loss of the USS Thresher|website=Iusscaa.org}}</ref>\n\nSubmarines typically rely on speed and deck angle ([[angle of attack]]) rather than deballasting to surface; they are propelled at an angle towards the surface. Ballast tanks were almost never blown at depth, and doing so could cause the submarine to rocket to the surface out of control. Normal procedure was to drive the submarine to [[periscope]] depth, raise the periscope to verify the area was clear, then blow the tanks and surface the submarine.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nAt the time, reactor-plant operating procedures did not allow for a rapid reactor restart following a scram, or even the ability to use steam remaining in the secondary system to propel the submarine to the surface. After a scram, standard procedure was to isolate the main steam system, cutting off the flow of steam to the turbines providing propulsion and electricity. This was done to prevent an over-rapid cool-down of the reactor. ''Thresher''{{'}}s reactor control officer, Lieutenant Raymond McCoole, was not at his station in the maneuvering room, or indeed on the boat, during the fatal dive. McCoole was at home caring for his wife who had been injured in a household accident&nbsp;\u2013 he had been all but ordered ashore by a sympathetic Commander Harvey. McCoole's trainee, Jim Henry, fresh from [[Naval Nuclear Power School|nuclear power school]], probably followed standard operating procedures and gave the order to isolate the steam system after the scram, even though ''Thresher'' was at or slightly below its maximum depth. Once closed, the large steam system isolation valves could not be reopened quickly. Reflecting on the situation in later life, McCoole was sure he would have delayed shutting the valves, thus allowing the boat to \"answer bells\" and drive itself to the surface, despite the flooding in the engineering spaces. [[Hyman G. Rickover|Admiral Rickover]] later changed the procedure, creating the \"Fast Recovery Startup\" procedure. The Fast Recovery Startup allows an immediate reactor restart and for steam to be withdrawn from the secondary system in limited quantities for several minutes following a scram.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nIn a dockside simulation of flooding in the engine room, held before ''Thresher'' sailed, it took the watch in charge 20 minutes to isolate a simulated leak in the auxiliary seawater system. At test depth with the reactor shut down, ''Thresher'' would not have had 20 minutes to recover. Even after isolating a short-circuit in the reactor controls, it would have taken nearly 10 minutes to restart the plant.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n''Thresher'' likely [[implosion (mechanical process)|imploded]] at a depth of {{convert|1300|-|2000|ft|m|abbr=on|order=flip}}.{{fact|date=July 2019}}\n\nThe U.S. Navy has periodically monitored the environmental conditions of the site since the sinking and has reported the results in an annual public report on environmental monitoring for U.S. Naval nuclear-powered craft. These reports provide specifics on the environmental sampling of [[sediment]], water, and marine life which was done to ascertain whether ''Thresher''{{'}}s nuclear reactor has had a significant effect on the deep ocean environment. The reports also explain the methodology for conducting deep-sea monitoring from both surface vessels and submersibles. The monitoring data confirm that there has been no significant effect on the environment. Nuclear fuel in the submarine remains intact.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nDeclassified information in December 2018 showed that [[United_States_Navy_Reserve|USNR]] Commander (Dr.) [[Robert Ballard]], the oceanographer credited with locating the wreck of {{RMS|Titanic}}, was sent by the Navy on a mission under cover of the search for ''Titanic'' to map and collect visual data on ''Thresher'' and {{USS|Scorpion|SSN-589|2}} wrecks.<ref>[http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/11/25/60minutes/main5773673.shtml The Great Explorer] ''[[60 Minutes]]''; aired 29 November 2009</ref>  Ballard had approached the Navy in 1982 for funding to find ''Titanic'' with his new deep-diving robot submersible. The Navy conditionally granted him the funds if the submarine wrecks were surveyed before ''Titanic''. Ballard's robotic survey showed that the depth ''Thresher'' had sunk caused implosion and total destruction; the only recoverable piece was a foot of marled pipe.<ref>''Lost Subs: Disaster at Sea''. Tim Kelly, Executive Producer. DVD. [[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]], 2002.</ref> His 1985 search for ''Scorpion'' revealed a large debris field \"as though it had been put through a shredding machine.\" His obligation to inspect the wrecks completed, and with the radioactive threat from both established as small, Ballard then searched for ''Titanic''. Financial limitations allowed him 12 days to search, and the debris-field search technique he had used for the two submarines was applied to locate ''Titanic''.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100604054238/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/us_and_americas/article3994955.ece : Titanic search was cover for secret Cold War subs mission] ''[[The Times]]'', 24 May 2008</ref>\n\nAlmost all records of the court of inquiry remain unavailable to the public. In 1998, the Navy began declassifying them, but decided in 2012 that it would not release them to the public. In February 2020, in response to a [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|FOIA]] lawsuit by military historian James Bryant, a federal court ordered the Navy to begin releasing documents by May 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Eatinger |first1=Robert |title=Fifty-Seven Years Later: America\u2019s Worst Nuclear Submarine Disaster |url=https://www.lawfareblog.com/fifty-seven-years-later-americas-worst-nuclear-submarine-disaster |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=[[Lawfare]] |date=10 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Disaster sequence of 10 April 1963==\n[[File:Ssn593thresher.gif|thumb|right|375px|Time-accelerated sequence of (hypothetical) events during the disaster]]\n[[File:Diagram of depth at Thresher Incident.tif|thumb|A diagram (roughly to scale) of the depth of the ocean where the incident and loss of Thresher took place.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Timeline of the ''Thresher'' disaster<ref>Bentley, John. ''The Thresher Disaster'', New York: Doubleday, 1975, pp. 157\u2013165</ref>\n! Time!!Event\n|-\n| 07:47 || ''Thresher'' begins its descent to the test depth of {{convert|1000|ft|m|abbr=on|order=flip}}.\n|-\n| 07:52 || ''Thresher'' levels off at {{convert|400|ft|m|abbr=on|order=flip}}, contacts the surface, and the crew inspects the ship for leaks. None are found.\n|-\n| 08:09 || Commander Harvey reports reaching half the test depth.\n|-\n| 08:25 || ''Thresher'' reaches {{convert|1000|ft|m|abbr=on|order=flip}}.\n|-\n| 09:02 || ''Thresher'' is cruising at just a few knots (submarines normally move slowly and cautiously at great depths, lest a sudden jam of the diving planes send the ship below test depth in a matter of seconds.) The boat is descending in slow circles, and announces to ''Skylark'' she is turning to \"Corpen [course] 090.\" At this point, transmission quality from ''Thresher'' begins to noticeably degrade, possibly as a result of [[thermocline]]s.\n|-\n| 09:09 || As an unproven hypothesis that is disputed by acoustic data, the Navy's official investigation stated the likelihood of a brazed pipe-joint rupturing in the engine room. The crew would have attempted to stop the leak; at the same time, the engine room would be filling with a cloud of mist. Under the circumstances, Commander Harvey's likely decision would have been to order full speed, full rise on the fairwater planes, and blowing main ballast in order to surface. The pressurized air rapidly expanding in the pipes [[Joule-Thomson effect|cools down]], condensing moisture and depositing it on intended-as temporary strainers installed in the system to protect the moving parts of the valves during new-construction (should have been removed prior to sea trials)<ref>https://www.usni.org/magazines/proceedings/2018/july/declassify-thresher-data</ref>; in only a few seconds the moisture freezes, clogging the strainers and blocking the air flow, halting the effort to blow ballast. Water leaking from the broken pipe most likely causes short circuits leading to an automatic [[scram|shutdown]] of the ship's reactor, causing a loss of propulsion. The logical action at this point would have been for Harvey to order propulsion shifted to a battery-powered backup system. As soon as the flooding was contained, the engine room crew would have begun to restart the reactor, an operation that would be expected to take at least 7&nbsp;minutes.\n|-\n| 09:12 || ''Skylark'' pages ''Thresher'' on the underwater telephone: \"Gertrude [[underwater telephone]] check, K [over].\" With no immediate response (although ''Skylark'' is still unaware of the conditions aboard ''Thresher''), the signal \"K\" is repeated twice.\n|-\n| 09:13 || Harvey reports status via underwater telephone. The transmission is garbled, though some words are recognizable: \"[We are] experiencing minor difficulty, have positive up-angle, attempting to blow.\" The submarine, as a hypothesis, growing heavier from water flooding the engine room, continues its descent, probably tail-first. Another attempt to empty the ballast tanks is performed, again failing due to the formation of ice. Officers on ''Skylark'' could hear the hiss of compressed air over the loudspeaker at this point.\n|-\n| 09:14 || ''Skylark'' acknowledges with a brisk, \"Roger, out,\" awaiting further updates from the SSN. A follow-up message, \"No contacts in area,\" is sent to reassure ''Thresher'' she can surface quickly, without fear of collision, if required.\n|-\n| 09:15 || ''Skylark'' queries ''Thresher'' about her intentions: \"My course 270 degrees. Interrogative range and bearing from you.\" There is no response, and ''Skylark''{{'}}s captain, Lieutenant Commander Hecker, sends his own Gertrude underwater telephone message to the submarine, \"Are you in control?\"\n|-\n| 09:16 || ''Skylark'' picks up a garbled transmission from ''Thresher'', transcribed in the ship's log as \"900 N.\" (The meaning of this message is unclear, and was not discussed at the inquiry; it may have indicated the submarine's depth and course, or it may have referred to a navy \"event number\" (1000 indicating loss of submarine), with the \"N\" signifying a negative response to the query from ''Skylark'', \"Are you in control?\")\n|-\n| 09:17 || A second transmission is received, with the partially recognizable phrase \"exceeding test depth ... \" The (hypothetical) leak from the broken pipe grows with increased pressure.\n|-\n| 09:18 || ''Skylark'' detects a high-energy, low-frequency noise, characteristic of an implosion.\n|-\n| 09:20 || ''Skylark'' continues to page ''Thresher'', repeatedly calling for a radio check, a smoke bomb, or some other indication of the boat's condition.\n|-\n| 11:04 || ''Skylark'' attempts to transmit a message to COMSUBLANT (Commander, Submarines, Atlantic Fleet): \"Unable to communicate with ''Thresher'' since 0917R. Have been calling by [[underwater telephone|UQC]] voice and [[Morse code|CW]], QHB, CW every minute. Explosive signals every 10 minutes with no success. Last transmission received was garbled. Indicated Thresher was approaching test depth ... Conducting expanding search.\" Radio problems meant that COMSUBLANT did not receive and respond to this message until 12:45. Hecker initiated \"Event SUBMISS [loss of a submarine]\" procedures at 11:21, and continued to repeatedly hail ''Thresher'' until after 17:00.\n|}\n\nDuring the 1963 inquiry, Admiral [[Hyman Rickover]] stated:\n\n<blockquote>I believe the loss of the Thresher should not be viewed solely as the result of failure of a specific braze, weld, system or component, but rather should be considered a consequence of the philosophy of design, construction and inspection that has been permitted in our naval shipbuilding programs. I think it is important that we re-evaluate our present practices where, in the desire to make advancements, we may have forsaken the fundamentals of good engineering.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://engineering.vanderbilt.edu/news/2013/vanderbilt-ties-to-%E2%80%98worst-submarine-tragedy%E2%80%99-50-years-ago/ |title=Vanderbilt ties to 'worst submarine tragedy' 50 years ago |publisher=School of Engineering, Vanderbilt University |date=2013 |accessdate=23 April 2013}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Alternative theory of the sinking: electrical failure==\nOn 8 April 2013, Bruce Rule, an acoustic data expert, published his own analysis of the data collected by USS ''Skylark'' and Atlantic [[SOSUS]] arrays in a paper<ref>[http://www.designed4submariners.com/uploads/Docs_Thresher_and_Scorpion_Loss.pdf \"What Sank The Thresher\"], Bruce Rule, 10 April 2013</ref> in the ''Navy Times''.<ref>[http://www.navytimes.com/article/20130404/NEWS/304040021/50-years-later-look-what-really-sank-Thresher \"50 years later, a look at what really sank the ''Thresher''\"], Bruce Rule and [[Norman Polmar]], 4 April 2013 (''Navy Times'' link)</ref><ref name=\"navtimespdf\">[http://www.designed4submariners.com/uploads/Thresher_Report.pdf \"What Sank The Thresher\"], Bruce Rule and [[Norman Polmar]], 8 April 2013</ref> Rule based his analysis on SOSUS data that was highly classified in 1963 and was not discussed in open session of the Court of Inquiry and was not revealed at the congressional hearings.<ref name=\"navtimespdf\"/>  A retired Navy captain and former commanding officer of the same class of submarine as ''Thresher'', citing Rule's findings, has called for the U.S. government to declassify the data associated with the boat's sinking, and presented an alternative disaster sequence based upon the acoustic data.<ref>https://www.usni.org/magazines/proceedings/2018/july/declassify-thresher-data</ref><ref>https://www.kitsapsun.com/story/news/2019/07/16/retired-navy-captain-believes-time-now-release-thresher-records/1738878001/</ref>\n\nRule concluded that the primary cause of the sinking was a failure of the electrical bus that powered the main coolant pumps. According to Rule, SOSUS data indicates that after two minutes of electrical instability, the bus failed at 9:11&nbsp;a.m., causing the main coolant pumps to trip off. This caused an immediate reactor scram, resulting in a loss of propulsion. ''Thresher'' could not be deballasted because ice had formed in the high-pressure air pipes, and so she sank. Rule's analysis holds that flooding (whether from a silver brazed joint or anywhere else) played no role in the reactor scram or the sinking, and that ''Thresher'' was intact until she imploded. In addition to the SOSUS data that does not record any sound of flooding, the crew of ''Skylark'' did not report hearing any noise that sounded like flooding, and ''Skylark'' was able to communicate with ''Thresher'', despite the fact that, at test depth, even a small leak would have produced a deafening roar. Additionally, the previous commander of ''Thresher'' testified that he would not have described flooding, even from a small-diameter pipe, as a \"minor problem\".<ref name=\"navtimespdf\"/>\n\nRule interprets the communication \"900\" from ''Thresher'' at 9:17&nbsp;a.m. as a reference to test depth, signifying that ''Thresher'' was {{convert|900|ft|order=flip}} below her test depth of {{convert|1,300|ft|order=flip}}, or {{convert|2,200|ft|order=flip}} below sea level. According to Rule the SOSUS data indicates an implosion of ''Thresher'' at 09:18:24, at a depth of {{convert|2,400|ft|order=flip}}, {{convert|400|ft|order=flip}} below her predicted collapse depth. The implosion took 0.1 seconds, too fast for the human nervous system to perceive.<ref name=\"navtimespdf\"/>\n\n==SUBSAFE legacy==\nWhen the Court of Inquiry delivered its final report, it recommended that the Navy implement a more rigorous program of design review and safety inspections during construction. That program, launched in December 1963, was known as [[SUBSAFE]]. From 1915 to 1963, the U.S. Navy lost a total of 16 submarines to non-combat accidents. Since the inception of SUBSAFE only one submarine has suffered a similar fate, and that was {{USS|Scorpion|SSN-589|6}}, which sank in 1968 for reasons still undetermined. ''Scorpion'' was not SUBSAFE certified.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seacoastonline.com/articles/20130324-NEWS-303240357 |title=USS Thresher Left Legacy of Safety for Submarines|publisher=SeaCoast online |date=24 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Memorials==\n[[File:6707-ArlingtonCemetary-USS ThresherMemorialStone.png|thumb|right|upright|Memorial stone for a lost USS ''Thresher'' sailor, [[Arlington National Cemetery]], July 1967]]\n[[File:USS_Thresher_memorial_dedication_at_Arlington.jpg|thumb|right|USS ''Thresher'' memorial dedication at [[Arlington National Cemetery]], September 26, 2019]]\n\n=== Permanent ===\n* The chapel at [[Portsmouth Navy Yard]], where the submarine was built, was renamed ''Thresher'' Memorial Chapel.<ref>{{cite book|first=Richard E. |last=Winslow III|title=Portsmouth-Built: Submarines of the Portsmouth Naval Shipyard |page=161|publisher=Portsmouth Marine Society|year=1985|isbn=091581904X}}</ref>\n* In [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire]], there is a stone memorial with a plaque honoring all who were lost on ''Thresher''. It is outside the {{USS|Albacore|AGSS-569|2}} museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WM52XP |title=Wreck of USS Thresher (SSN-593)&nbsp;\u2013 Portsmouth, NH&nbsp;\u2013 Disaster Memorials on |website=Waymarking.com |accessdate=1 June 2010}}</ref>\n* Just outside the main gate of the Naval Weapons Station, [[Seal Beach, California]], a ''Thresher''-''Scorpion'' Memorial honors the crews of the two submarines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.submarinehistory.com/ThresherScorpionMemorial.html |title=ThresherScorpionMemorial |website=Submarinehistory.com |accessdate=1 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100518151910/http://www.submarinehistory.com/ThresherScorpionMemorial.html |archivedate=18 May 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* In [[Eureka, Missouri]], there is a marble stone at the post office on Thresher Drive honoring the \"officers and crew of the USS ''Thresher,'' lost 10 April 1963.\"<ref>[http://www.eureka.mo.us/MINUTES/2007PARK_BOARD/Park_Board_Minutes_4-10-07.pdf Park Board Minutes 04-10-2007] (pdf file) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080626170105/http://www.eureka.mo.us/MINUTES/2007PARK_BOARD/Park_Board_Minutes_4-10-07.pdf |date=26 June 2008}}</ref>\n* [[Salisbury, Massachusetts]], named Robert E. Steinel Memorial Park in honor of ''Thresher'' crewman and Salisbury resident Sonarman First Class Robert Edwin Steinel.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.seacoastonline.com/article/20130120/News/301200337 |title=Thresher victim, a young father, remembered |first=D. Allan |last=Kerr |website=seacoastonline.com |date=January 20, 2013 |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\n* In [[Nutley, New Jersey]], there is a monument to ''Thresher'' crewmember Pervis Robison, Jr.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nutley NJ USS Thresher Memorial|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/sheenachi/145949526/|publisher=Flickr|accessdate=13 August 2016}}</ref>\n* In [[Denville, New Jersey]], there is a monument to ''Thresher'' crewmember Robert D. Kearney at the Gardner Field recreation area.<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert D. Kearney Memorial marker|url=https://www.google.com/maps/@40.8976936,-74.4845036,3a,75y,90t/data=!3m8!1e2!3m6!1s-yhukrjLucZE%2FWSHoH9jyHNI%2FAAAAAAABZXA%2FVTtli-_LA3kVi931pHtIJv9QJBNZ33NZwCLIB!2e4!3e12!6s%2F%2Flh4.googleusercontent.com%2F-yhukrjLucZE%2FWSHoH9jyHNI%2FAAAAAAABZXA%2FVTtli-_LA3kVi931pHtIJv9QJBNZ33NZwCLIB%2Fw203-h270-k-no%2F!7i3024!8i4032|publisher=GoogleMaps|accessdate=21 May 2017}}</ref>\n* Thresher Avenue, named for the submarine, serves a residential area in [[Naval Base Kitsap]] in Washington state.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://goo.gl/maps/XyMALFzNGtn |title=Thresher Ave |website=[[Google Maps]] |accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* A {{convert|129|ft|adj=on}} flagpole at Kittery Memorial Circle in the town of [[Kittery, Maine]], was dedicated on 7 April 2013, the 50th anniversary of the loss of ''Thresher'', to honor the 129 lost souls''.''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kitteryrotaryafterhours.org/thresher-flagpole |title=Thresher Flagpole |website=kitteryrotaryafterhours.org |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\n* There is also a ''Thresher'' monument in Memorial Park next to the Kittery Town Hall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kitteryrotaryafterhours.org/memorial-park|title=Memorial Park|website=kitteryrotaryafterhours.org|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* There is a memorial monument to the submariners lost in the ''Thresher'' and ''Scorpion'' located on Point Pleasant Road in [[Mount Pleasant, South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.https://www.hmdb.org/marker |title=HMdb.org THE HISTORICAL MARKER DATABASE |website=hmdb.org/marker |accessdate=May 30, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Naval Submarine Base New London]] in [[Groton, Connecticut]], named an enlisted barracks \"Thresher Hall\" after the submarine,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.subasect.com/directory/bachelor-housing |title=Bachelor Housing |website=subasect.com |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> and mounted a plaque in its lobby displaying the names of the crew members, shipyard government employees and contractors that were lost.<ref>https://www.ussthresher.com/roster/</ref>{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n* A [[joint resolution]] was introduced during the [[107th United States Congress]] in 2001 calling for the erection of a memorial in [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/uss-thresher.htm|title=USS Thresher Disaster|last=Robert Patterson|first=Michael|website=Arlingtoncemetery.net|accessdate=1 June 2010}}</ref> The formal commemorative monument approval process for Arlington, which began in 2012, received final approval in January 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wmtw.com/article/uss-thresher-memorial-to-be-built-at-arlington-national-cemetery/26073478 |title=USS Thresher memorial to be built at Arlington National Cemetery |website=[[WMTW]] |date=January 29, 2019}}</ref><ref name=fostersJan2019>{{cite news |url=https://www.fosters.com/news/20190129/uss-thresher-memorial-approved-for-arlington-national |title=USS Thresher memorial approved for Arlington National |first=Hadley |last=Barndollar |website=[[Foster's Daily Democrat]] |location=[[Dover, New Hampshire]] |date=January 29, 2019 |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> The memorial was approved on January 28, 2019, by the Secretary of the Army, [[Mark Esper]].<ref>https://threshermemorial.org/</ref> While a few crew members already had memorials at Arlington, this became the first tribute there to the boat's entire crew and her other passengers.<ref name=fostersJan2019/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.usni.org/2019/01/31/army-set-approve-uss-thresher-memorial-arlington-national-cemetery |title=Army Set to Approve USS Thresher Memorial at Arlington National Cemetery |first=John |last=Grady |website=USNI News |date=January 31, 2019}}</ref> The memorial was dedicated on September 26, 2019.<ref name=fostersJanWaPo2019>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/history/2019/09/26/nuclear-submarine-thresher-was-said-be-americas-best-then-tragedy-struck/ |title=The nuclear submarine Thresher was said to be America\u2019s best. Then tragedy struck. |first=Michael E.|last=Ruane|website=[[The Washington Post]] |location=[[Washington, D.C.]] |date=September 26, 2019 |accessdate=September 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fosters.com/news/20190926/tears-in-my-eyes-uss-thresher-memorial-dedicated |title=\u2018Tears in my eyes\u2019: USS Thresher memorial dedicated |first=Trent |last=Spiner |website=[[Foster's Daily Democrat]] |location=[[Dover, New Hampshire]] |date=September 26, 2019 |accessdate=September 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Former\n* In [[Carpentersville, Illinois]], the Dundee Township Park District named a swimming facility (now closed and demolished) in honor of ''Thresher''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dtpd.org/rccms/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/DTPD-Timeline.pdf |title=Brief Timeline of the Dundee Township Park District |website=dtpd.org |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Other ===\n*On 12 April 1963, President [[John F. Kennedy]] issued {{Executive Order|11104}} paying tribute to the crew of ''Thresher'' by ordering all national flags to half-staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051115062550/http://www.lib.umich.edu/govdocs/jfkeo/eo/11104.htm|title=Executive Order 11104|date=15 November 2005|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=22 October 2018}}</ref>\n* Five folk music groups or artists have produced songs memorializing ''Thresher''; \"Ballad Of The Thresher\", by [[The Kingston Trio]], \"The Thresher Disaster\", by [[Tom Paxton]]; \"The Thresher\", by [[Phil Ochs]], \"The Thresher\", by [[Pete Seeger]], and \"Thresher\", by [[Shovels & Rope]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oldsaltblog.com/2013/04/four-ballads-of-the-uss-thresher/ |title=Four Ballads of the USS Thresher |first=Rick |last=Spilman |website=oldsaltblog.com |date=April 14, 2013 |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2014/08/17/339586770/first-listen-shovels-rope-swimmin-time |title=First Listen: Shovels & Rope, 'Swimmin' Time'|first=Ann |last=Powers |website=npr.org |date=August 17, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Deep Submergence Rescue Vehicle]]\n* {{USS|Scorpion|SSN-589}}, the only other American nuclear-powered submarine to be lost at sea\n* [[John P. Craven]], a key individual in the search for ''Thresher''\n* [[Kursk submarine disaster|''Kursk'' submarine disaster]], next largest loss of life on a submarine\n* [[List of sunken nuclear submarines]]\n* [[List of lost United States submarines]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* One of the earliest and most comprehensive accounts of the loss of the ''Thresher'' was written by Vice Admiral E.W. Grenfell, Commander Submarine Force Atlantic, and published in March 1964 in the U.S. Navy's professional journal ''Proceedings''; on 1 April 2013, on the occasion of the 50th anniversary, the U.S. Naval Institute has re-posted Admiral Grenfell's detailed account: {{cite web|url=http://www.navalhistory.org/2013/04/01/uss-thresher-ssn-593-3-august-1961-10-april-1963|title=USS Thresher (SSN-593) 3 August 1961 \u2013 10 April 1963}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040804224339/http://www.submarinehistory.com/Thresher.html Loss of USS ''Thresher'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100518151910/http://www.submarinehistory.com/ThresherScorpionMemorial.html ''Thresher-Scorpion'' Memorial]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110927013845/http://www.submarinehistory.com/WWIISubmarineMemorial.html World War II National Submarine Memorial&nbsp;\u2013 West]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110927013857/http://www.submarinehistory.com/WWIISubmarineMemorial-East.html World War II National Submarine Memorial&nbsp;\u2013 East]\n* {{cite book |last=Sontag |first=Sherry |first2= Christopher|last2= Drew|first3=Annette Lawrence |last3=Drew |title=[[Blind Man's Bluff: The Untold Story of American Submarine Espionage]] |publisher=HarperPaperbacks |location=New York |year=1999 |isbn=0-06-103004-X}}\n* {{cite book |last=Polmar |first=Norman |authorlink=Norman Polmar |title=Death of the Thresher |publisher=Chilton Books |location=Philadelphia |year=1964 |isbn=1-58574-348-8 |url=https://archive.org/details/deathofussthresh00norm }} First published 1964; reissued in 2001 by Lyons Press (Guilford, Conn) as ''The Death of the USS Thresher''\n* {{cite book |last=Bentley |first=John |title=The Thresher Disaster: The Most Tragic Dive in Submarine History |publisher=Doubleday |location=Garden City, N.Y |year=1975 |isbn=0-385-03057-6 |url=https://archive.org/details/thresherdisaster00bent }}\n* {{cite book |last=Rockwell |first=Theodore |title=The Rickover Effect: How One Man made a Difference |publisher=IUniverse |location=Lincoln |year=2002 |isbn=0-595-74527-X }}\n* [https://archive.is/20130201132002/http://archiver.rootsweb.com/th/read/USS-THRESHER-SSN593/2005-01/1104944120 McCoole's statement re: shutting main steam valves during reactor scram]\n* {{cite book|last=DiMercurio|first=Michael|title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to Submarines|year=2003|publisher=Alpha Books |location=Indianapolis|isbn=978-0-02-864471-4|last2=Benson|first2=Michael}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author=Joint Committee on Atomic Energy (United States Congress)|title=Loss of the U.S.S. \"Thresher\": Hearings, Eighty-eighth Congress, first and second sessions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uKAJmmtgIUEC|accessdate=5 April 2013|year=1965 |publisher=Govt. Print. Off.}}\n* U.S. Atlantic Fleet. Staff, Deputy Commander Submarine Force. (1964) United States Ship Thresher (SSN 593): In memoriam 10 April 1963. U.S. Navy Atlantic Fleet. No Available ISBN.\n* ''Thresher''{{'}}s ship number 593 is interesting as a \"good\" prime number, as discussed at [[593 (number)|593]].\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|USS Thresher (SSN-593)}}\n* [http://www.oneternalpatrol.com/uss-thresher-593.htm On Eternal Patrol: USS ''Thresher'']\n* [http://www.navsource.org/archives/08/08593.htm Photo gallery of ''Thresher'' at NavSource.org]\n* http://www.ussthresher.com/\n* http://www.thresherbase.org/\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r0bRA1hp23w Memorial Video on YouTube]\n\n{{Permit class submarine}}\n{{1963 shipwrecks}}\n{{coord|41|46|N|65|03|W|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thresher (Ssn-593)}}\n[[Category:United States submarine accidents]]\n[[Category:Permit-class submarines]]\n[[Category:Cold War submarines of the United States]]\n[[Category:Lost submarines of the United States]]\n[[Category:Sunken nuclear submarines]]\n[[Category:Nuclear submarines of the United States Navy|Thresher, USS]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1963]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks in the Atlantic Ocean|Thresher, USS]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Kittery, Maine]]\n[[Category:1960 ships]]\n[[Category:1963 in the United States]]\n[[Category:Ships lost with all hands]]\n", "text_old": "{{other ships|USS Thresher}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=[[File:USS Thresher;0859306.jpg|300px|USS Thresher (SSN-593) underway, 30 April 1961]]\n|Ship caption=USS ''Thresher'' (SSN-593) underway, 30 April 1961\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1963}}\n|Ship name=''Thresher''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship ordered=15 January 1958\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder=[[Portsmouth Naval Shipyard]]\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=28 May 1958\n|Ship launched=9 July 1960\n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=3 August 1961\n|Ship recommissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship maiden voyage=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship motto=''Vis Tacita'' (Silent Strength)\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship fate=Lost with all hands during deep diving tests, 10 April 1963; 129 died.\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{Sclass-|Thresher|submarine}}\n|Ship displacement={{convert|3540|ST|t|abbr=on}} light, {{convert|3770|ST|t|abbr=on}} submerged\n|Ship length={{convert|279|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|32|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draft={{convert|26|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion=1 Westinghouse [[S5W reactor|S5W PWR]], Westinghouse Geared Turbines {{convert|15,000|shp|MW|abbr=on}}\n|Ship speed={{convert|33|kn}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship test depth=\n|Ship boats=\n|Ship capacity=\n|Ship troops=\n|Ship complement=16 officers, 96 men\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=4 \u00d7 {{convert|21|in|mm|abbr=on}} [[torpedo tube]]s amidships\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\nThe second '''USS ''Thresher'' (SSN-593)''' was the [[lead boat]] of [[Permit-class submarine|her class]] of nuclear-powered attack [[submarine]]s in the [[United States Navy]]. She was the U.S. Navy's [[USS Thresher (SS-200)|second submarine]] to be named after the [[thresher shark]].\n\nOn 10 April 1963, ''Thresher'' sank during deep-diving tests about {{convert|220|mi|km|abbr=on|order=flip}} east of Boston, Massachusetts, killing all 129 crew and shipyard personnel aboard. It is the second-deadliest submarine incident on record, after the loss of the French submarine [[French submarine Surcouf|''Surcouf'']], in which 130 crew died.<ref name=\"deadliest1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.naval-technology.com/features/featureperil-in-the-depths-the-worlds-worst-submarine-disasters-4191027/ |last=Duddu|first=Praveen|title=Peril in the depths \u2013 the world's worst submarine disasters |website=Navaltechnology.com |date= 6 March 2014 |accessdate=7 August 2018 }}</ref><ref name=Polmar /> Her loss was a watershed for the U.S. Navy, leading to the implementation of a rigorous submarine safety program known as [[SUBSAFE]]. The first [[List of sunken nuclear submarines|nuclear submarine lost at sea]], ''Thresher'' was also the third of four submarine losses that killed over 100 aboard; the others being the [[USS Argonaut (SM-1)|Argonaut]], lost with 102 aboard in World War II, the Surcouf, and the ''[[Kursk submarine disaster|Kursk]]'', which sank with 118 aboard in 2000.\n\n==Significance of design and loss==\nCreated to find and destroy [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] submarines, ''Thresher'' was the fastest and quietest submarine of the day, matching the smaller, contemporary {{sclass-|Skipjack|submarine|4}}. She also had the most advanced weapons system, including launchers for the U.S. Navy's newest [[anti-submarine missile]], the [[UUM-44 SUBROC|SUBROC]], as well as passive and active sonar that could detect vessels at unprecedented range. Shortly after her loss, the [[COMSUBLANT#Officers serving as COMSUBLANT|Commander of Submarine Force Atlantic]] wrote in the March 1964 issue of the [[U.S. Naval Institute]]'s monthly journal ''Proceedings'' that \"the Navy had depended upon this performance to the extent that it had asked for and received authority to build 14 of these ships, as well as an additional 11 submarines with very much the same characteristics. This was the first time since World War II that we had considered our design sufficiently advanced to embark upon construction of a large class of general-purpose attack submarines.\"{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nFollowing Navy tradition, this class of subs was originally named ''Thresher'' after the lead boat.  When ''Thresher'' was struck from the [[Naval Vessel Register]] on 16 April 1963, the class name was changed to that of the second boat, {{USS|Permit|SSN-594|2}}, and ''Thresher'' is now officially referred to as a [[Permit-class submarine|''Permit''-class submarine]]. Having been \"lost at sea\", ''Thresher'' was not decommissioned by the U.S. Navy and remains on \"Eternal Patrol\".{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n==Early career==\n[[File:USS Thresher (SSN-593) bow.jpg|thumb|left|''Thresher'' at sea on 24 July 1961]]\nThe contract to build ''Thresher'' was awarded to [[Portsmouth Naval Shipyard]] on 15 January 1958, and her [[keel]] was laid on 28 May 1958. She was [[ship naming and launching|launched]] on 9 July 1960, was sponsored by Mrs. Mary B. Warder<ref name=Polmar>{{cite book |title=The Death of the USS Thresher: The Story Behind History's Deadliest Submarine Disaster |author=Polmar, Norman |authorlink=Norman Polmar |isbn=978-1592283927}}</ref> (wife of [[World War II]] skipper Frederick B. Warder), and was [[ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 3 August 1961, [[Commander (United States)|Commander]] Dean L. Axene commanding.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n''Thresher'' conducted lengthy sea trials in the western Atlantic and [[Caribbean Sea]] areas in 1961\u20131962. These tests allowed a thorough evaluation of her many new and complex technological features and weapons. She took part in Nuclear Submarine Exercise (NUSUBEX) 3\u201361 off the northeastern coast of the United States from 18\u201324 September 1961.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nOn 18 October 1961, ''Thresher,'' in company with the diesel-electric submarine {{USS|Cavalla|SS-244|2}}, headed south on a 3-week test and training cruise to [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], arriving 2 November. Following customary procedure while in port, her reactor was shut down. Since no shore power connection was available in San Juan, the ship's backup [[diesel generator]] was used to carry the [[Hotel electric power|\"hotel\" electrical loads]]. Several hours later, the backup generator broke down and the electrical load was transferred to the ship's battery.  As most of the battery power was needed to keep vital systems operating and to restart the reactor, lighting and air conditioning were shut down. Without air conditioning, temperature and humidity in the submarine rose, reaching {{convert|60|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|abbr=on}} after about 10 hours. The crew attempted to repair the diesel generator (four men would receive [[Commendation Medal|Navy commendation medals]] for their work that night). After it became apparent that the generator could not be fixed before the battery was depleted, the crew tried to restart the reactor, but the remaining battery charge was insufficient. The captain, returning to the ship from a shore function, arrived just after the battery ran down. The crew eventually borrowed cables from another ship in the harbor and connected them to the adjacent ''Cavalla'', which started her diesels and provided enough power to allow ''Thresher'' to restart her reactor.<ref>Polmar, pp. 13\u201317</ref>\n\n''Thresher'' conducted further trials and fired test [[torpedo]]es before returning to Portsmouth on 29 November 1961. The boat remained in port through the end of the year, and spent the first two months of 1962 evaluating her [[sonar]] and SUBROC systems. In March, she participated in NUSUBEX 2\u201362 (an exercise designed to improve the tactical capabilities of nuclear submarines) and in [[anti-submarine warfare]] training with Task Group ALPHA.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nOff [[Charleston, South Carolina]], ''Thresher'' undertook operations supporting development of the [[UUM-44 SUBROC|SUBROC anti-submarine missile]].  She returned briefly to [[New England]] waters, after which she proceeded to Florida for more SUBROC tests. While moored at [[Port Canaveral, Florida]], the submarine was accidentally struck by a tug, which damaged one of her [[ballast tanks]]. After repairs at [[Groton, Connecticut]], by the [[Electric Boat]] Company, ''Thresher'' went south for more tests and trials off [[Key West, Florida]], then returned northward. The submarine entered Portsmouth Shipyard on 16 July 1962 to begin a scheduled 6-month post-shakedown availability to examine systems and make repairs and corrections as necessary. As is typical with a first-of-class boat, the work took longer than expected, lasting nearly 9 months. The ship was finally recertified and undocked on 8 April 1963.<ref>[http://www.navalhistory.org/2013/04/01/uss-thresher-ssn-593-3-august-1961-10-april-1963 \"USS ''Thresher''\"], article by Vice Admiral E.W. Grenfell, ''U.S. Naval Institute Proceedings'', March 1964; accessed 6 April 2013.</ref>\n\n==Sinking==\nOn 9 April 1963, ''Thresher'', commanded by [[Lieutenant Commander]] John Wesley Harvey, got underway from Kittery, Maine at 08:00 and met with the submarine rescue ship {{USS|Skylark|ASR-20|2}} at 11:00 to begin her initial post-overhaul dive trials, in an area some {{convert|190|nmi|mi km|abbr=on|order=flip}} east of [[Cape Cod, Massachusetts]]. That afternoon ''Thresher'' conducted an initial trim dive test, surfaced, and then performed a second dive to half of test depth. She remained submerged overnight and re-established underwater communications with ''Skylark'' at 06:30 on 10 April to commence deep-dive trials. Following standard practice, ''Thresher'' slowly dove deeper as she traveled in circles under ''Skylark''&nbsp;\u2013 to remain within communications distance&nbsp;\u2013 pausing every {{convert|100|ft|abbr=on|order=flip}} of depth to check the integrity of all systems. As ''Thresher'' neared her test depth, ''Skylark'' received garbled communications over [[underwater telephone]] indicating \" ... &nbsp;minor difficulties, have positive up-angle, attempting to blow\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csp.navy.mil/othboats/593.htm |title=COMSUBPAC Web site, Submarines Lost or Damaged before and after World War II |accessdate=2 February 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060129171708/http://www.csp.navy.mil/othboats/593.htm |archivedate=29 January 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://usgovinfo.about.com/library/weekly/aa081700a.htm |title=U.S. Gov Info / Resources, US Navy's Submarine Rescue Team |accessdate=2 February 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/transcripts/2602subsecrets.html |title=NOVA Web site, transcript of \"Submarines, Secrets, and Spies\" |accessdate=2 February 2006}}</ref> and then a final even more garbled message that included the number \"900\".<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20131031061419/http://www.navsource.org/archives/08/08593b.htm Thresher (SSN 593) Loss & Inquiry], navsource.org</ref> When ''Skylark'' received no further communication, surface observers gradually realized ''Thresher'' had sunk.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nBy mid-afternoon, 15 Navy ships were en route to the search area. At 18:30, the Commander, Submarine Force Atlantic, sent word to Portsmouth Naval Shipyard to begin notifying the crew's family members, starting with Commander Harvey's wife, Irene Harvey, that ''Thresher'' was missing.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nBy morning on 11 April, all hope of finding ''Thresher'' was abandoned, and at 10:30, the Chief of Naval Operations Admiral [[George W. Anderson Jr.]], went before the press corps at [[the Pentagon]] to announce that the submarine was lost with all hands. President [[John F. Kennedy]] ordered all flags to be flown at half staff on 12\u201315 April in honor of the 129 lost submariners and shipyard personnel.<ref>{{cite web\n  |title=Executive Order 11104&nbsp;\u2013 U.S.S. Thresher\n  |author=John F. Kennedy\n  |authorlink=John F. Kennedy\n  |work=[[Executive order (United States)|Executive Order]]\n  |date=April 12, 1963 \n  |url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=59043\n}}</ref>\n\n==Search and recovery==\n[[File:Search for USS Thresher (SSN-593).jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|Search operations underway near the accident site, 15 April 1963]]\nThe Navy quickly mounted an extensive search with surface ships and support from the [[Naval Research Laboratory]] (NRL), with its deep-search capability. The laboratory's small acoustic research vessel, ''Rockville'', with a unique trainable search sonar, left on 12 April 1963 for the search area. That vessel was to be followed by other personnel with a deep-camera system. There {{ship|USS|Allegheny|ATA-179|2}}, {{ship|USNS|Mission Capistrano||2}}, and {{ship|USS|Prevail|AM-107|2}} were engaged in a close sonar search of an area {{cvt|10|nmi|km mi}} square. {{ship|RV|Atlantis II||2}}, {{ship|USNS|Robert D. Conrad|T-AGOR-3|2}}, and {{ship|USNS|James M. Gilliss|T-AGOR-4|2}} were investigating likely contacts found in the sonar search. The NRL deep-towed camera system and personnel later operated off ''James M. Gilliss'' with some success, finding debris later confirmed to be from ''Thresher''.<ref name=Bundage>{{cite report |last=Bundage |first=Walter|date=November 29, 1988 |title=NRL's Deep Sea Floor Search Era |pages=4\u201116 |url=https://archive.org/details/DTIC_ADA204011/page/n8/mode/1up/ |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> The [[bathyscaphe Trieste|bathyscaphe ''Trieste'']] was alerted on 11 April and brought from San Diego to Boston. It was deployed for two series of dives on the debris field; the first taking place from 24 to 30 June, the second from late August until early September. The equipment-handling capability of ''Gilliss'' proved inadequate, even hazardous, to handle the towed vehicle, and the entire search was paused in September.<ref name=Gennari>{{cite report |last=Gennari |first=J. J. |date=1 January 1967 |title=Center Well Installation of USNS ''Mizar'' (T-AGOR-11) |pages= |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Naval Research Laboratory  |url=https://archive.org/details/DTIC_AD0647494/mode/2up |accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=Sealift>{{cite magazine |date=July 1968 |title=Ship That Helped Locate ''Thresher'' Searching for ''Scorpion'' |magazine=Sealift Magazine |volume=18 |issue=7 |pages=3-5, 12-13 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sFsShLqioGAC&pg=PA3#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe inadequacy of the AGOR type for handling deep-towed search vehicles led to a search for a vessel of a size and configuration that could handle such equipment in a sheltered area. In late 1963 that search resulted in acquisition of {{USNS|Mizar|AGOR-11|2}}, with intent to eventually add a sheltered center well for deploying equipment.<ref name=Bundage/><ref name=Gennari/>\n\nThe 1964 search included ''Mizar'' with partial modifications but not a center well, {{ship|USS|Hoist|ARS-40|2}}, and [[Bathyscaphe Trieste II|''Trieste II'']], ''Trieste''{{'}}s successor. That submersible incorporated parts of the original bathyscaphe and was completed in early 1964. The bathyscaphe was placed on board {{USNS|Private Francis X. McGraw|T-AK-241|6}} and shipped to Boston. ''Mizar'' did have a system, Underwater Tracking Equipment (UTE), by which it could track its towed vehicle and planned to track ''Trieste''. ''Mizar'' sailed on 25 June to begin the deep search and found the wreck within two days. By July 22 most of the lost submarine had been  photographed.<ref name=Buchanan>{{cite report |last= Buchanan |first=C. L. |year=1972 |title=A Love Affair (reprinted in Bundage: NRL's Deep Sea Floor Search Era) |pages=13-15 |url=https://archive.org/details/DTIC_ADA204011/page/n16/mode/1up/ |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> In early August the entire task force returned to the area with the submersible. Its first two dives were unsuccessful, but on the third dive the UTE enabled placement of ''Trieste II'' on the wreck, at first not seeing wreckage because the bathyscaphe was sitting on it.<ref name=Buchanan/>\n\nThe shattered remains of ''Thresher''{{'}}s hull were on the sea floor, approximately {{convert|8400|ft|m|order=flip}} below the surface, in five major sections.<ref name=brand>{{cite journal |author=Brand, V |title=Submersibles&nbsp;\u2013 Manned and Unmanned. |journal=South Pacific Underwater Medicine Society Journal |volume=7 |issue=3 |year=1977 |issn=0813-1988 |oclc=16986801 |url=http://archive.rubicon-foundation.org/6154 |accessdate=10 July 2008}}</ref> Most of the debris had spread over an area of about {{convert|134000|m2|yd2}}. Major sections of ''Thresher'', including the [[sail (submarine)|sail]], sonar dome, bow section, engineering spaces section, operations spaces section, and the stern planes were found and photographed. One aspect of the search conducted that summer by ''Mizar'' involved the use of highly sensitive [[proton magnetometer]]s furnished by the Instrument Division of [[Varian Associates]] in Palo Alto, and shipped aboard ''Mizar'' before her departure from NRL in Washington. The magnetometers were used in conjunction with underwater video cameras and suspended on the same electrical line used to tow the video cameras themselves.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/our-collections/photography/numerical-list-of-images/nhhc-series/nh-series/NH-97000/NH-97555.html|title=Loss of USS Thresher|website=History.navy.mil}}</ref>\n\n''Trieste II'' was commanded by Lieutenant John B. Mooney Jr., with co-pilot Lieutenant John H. Howland and Captain Frank Andrews in an operation that recovered bits of wreckage in September 1964. The groundbreaking deep submergence operations helped in the design and construction of other deep-diving submersibles which could be used in rescuing crews and recovering objects from submarines in distress below levels reachable by conventional methods.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n==Cause==\nDeep-sea photography, recovered artifacts, and an evaluation of her design and operational history permitted a court of inquiry to conclude ''Thresher'' had probably suffered the failure of a salt-water piping system joint which relied heavily on [[silver brazing]] instead of welding.  Earlier tests using ultrasound equipment found potential problems with about 14% of the tested brazed joints,<ref>[http://www.navsea.navy.mil/NewsView.aspx?nw=NewsWires&id=224 50 Years of Steely Purpose-USS Thresher Remembered] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130626170831/http://www.navsea.navy.mil/NewsView.aspx?nw=NewsWires&id=224 |date=26 June 2013 }}. Navsea.navy.mil. 10 April 2013.</ref> most of which were determined not to pose a risk significant enough to require a repair. High-pressure water spraying from a broken pipe joint may have shorted out one of the many electrical panels, causing a shutdown (\"[[scram]]\") of the reactor, which in turn caused loss of propulsion. The inability to blow the ballast tanks was later attributed to excessive moisture in the submarine's high-pressure air flasks, moisture which froze and plugged the flasks' flowpaths while passing through the valves. This was later simulated in dock-side tests on ''Thresher''{{'}}s sister sub, {{USS|Tinosa|SSN-606|2}}. During a test to simulate blowing ballast at or near [[test depth]], ice formed on strainers installed in valves; the flow of air lasted only a few seconds.<ref>[http://www.navsource.org/archives/08/08593b.htm Thresher (SSN-593)  Loss & Inquiry] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031061419/http://www.navsource.org/archives/08/08593b.htm |date=31 October 2013 }}. Navsource.org</ref> Air dryers were later retrofitted to the high-pressure air compressors, beginning with ''Tinosa'', to permit the emergency blow system to operate properly.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nSubsequent study of [[SOSUS]] (sound surveillance system) data from the time of the incident has given rise to doubts of whether flooding preceded the reactor scram, as no impact sounds of the high pressure water in the compartments of the submarine could be detected on instrument recordings from SOSUS at the time.  Such flooding would have been a significant sonic event, and no evidence of that can be found in the recorded data.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iusscaa.org/articles/brucerule/letter_to_the_deputy_cno.htm|title=Information and Security Issues Associated with the Loss of the USS Thresher|website=Iusscaa.org}}</ref>\n\nSubmarines typically rely on speed and deck angle ([[angle of attack]]) rather than deballasting to surface; they are propelled at an angle towards the surface. Ballast tanks were almost never blown at depth, and doing so could cause the submarine to rocket to the surface out of control. Normal procedure was to drive the submarine to [[periscope]] depth, raise the periscope to verify the area was clear, then blow the tanks and surface the submarine.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nAt the time, reactor-plant operating procedures did not allow for a rapid reactor restart following a scram, or even the ability to use steam remaining in the secondary system to propel the submarine to the surface. After a scram, standard procedure was to isolate the main steam system, cutting off the flow of steam to the turbines providing propulsion and electricity. This was done to prevent an over-rapid cool-down of the reactor. ''Thresher''{{'}}s reactor control officer, Lieutenant Raymond McCoole, was not at his station in the maneuvering room, or indeed on the boat, during the fatal dive. McCoole was at home caring for his wife who had been injured in a household accident&nbsp;\u2013 he had been all but ordered ashore by a sympathetic Commander Harvey. McCoole's trainee, Jim Henry, fresh from [[Naval Nuclear Power School|nuclear power school]], probably followed standard operating procedures and gave the order to isolate the steam system after the scram, even though ''Thresher'' was at or slightly below its maximum depth. Once closed, the large steam system isolation valves could not be reopened quickly. Reflecting on the situation in later life, McCoole was sure he would have delayed shutting the valves, thus allowing the boat to \"answer bells\" and drive itself to the surface, despite the flooding in the engineering spaces. [[Hyman G. Rickover|Admiral Rickover]] later changed the procedure, creating the \"Fast Recovery Startup\" procedure. The Fast Recovery Startup allows an immediate reactor restart and for steam to be withdrawn from the secondary system in limited quantities for several minutes following a scram.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nIn a dockside simulation of flooding in the engine room, held before ''Thresher'' sailed, it took the watch in charge 20 minutes to isolate a simulated leak in the auxiliary seawater system. At test depth with the reactor shut down, ''Thresher'' would not have had 20 minutes to recover. Even after isolating a short-circuit in the reactor controls, it would have taken nearly 10 minutes to restart the plant.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n''Thresher'' likely [[implosion (mechanical process)|imploded]] at a depth of {{convert|1300|-|2000|ft|m|abbr=on|order=flip}}.{{fact|date=July 2019}}\n\nThe U.S. Navy has periodically monitored the environmental conditions of the site since the sinking and has reported the results in an annual public report on environmental monitoring for U.S. Naval nuclear-powered craft. These reports provide specifics on the environmental sampling of [[sediment]], water, and marine life which was done to ascertain whether ''Thresher''{{'}}s nuclear reactor has had a significant effect on the deep ocean environment. The reports also explain the methodology for conducting deep-sea monitoring from both surface vessels and submersibles. The monitoring data confirm that there has been no significant effect on the environment. Nuclear fuel in the submarine remains intact.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nDeclassified information in December 2018 showed that [[United_States_Navy_Reserve|USNR]] Commander (Dr.) [[Robert Ballard]], the oceanographer credited with locating the wreck of {{RMS|Titanic}}, was sent by the Navy on a mission under cover of the search for ''Titanic'' to map and collect visual data on ''Thresher'' and {{USS|Scorpion|SSN-589|2}} wrecks.<ref>[http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/11/25/60minutes/main5773673.shtml The Great Explorer] ''[[60 Minutes]]''; aired 29 November 2009</ref>  Ballard had approached the Navy in 1982 for funding to find ''Titanic'' with his new deep-diving robot submersible. The Navy conditionally granted him the funds if the submarine wrecks were surveyed before ''Titanic''. Ballard's robotic survey showed that the depth ''Thresher'' had sunk caused implosion and total destruction; the only recoverable piece was a foot of marled pipe.<ref>''Lost Subs: Disaster at Sea''. Tim Kelly, Executive Producer. DVD. [[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]], 2002.</ref> His 1985 search for ''Scorpion'' revealed a large debris field \"as though it had been put through a shredding machine.\" His obligation to inspect the wrecks completed, and with the radioactive threat from both established as small, Ballard then searched for ''Titanic''. Financial limitations allowed him 12 days to search, and the debris-field search technique he had used for the two submarines was applied to locate ''Titanic''.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100604054238/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/us_and_americas/article3994955.ece : Titanic search was cover for secret Cold War subs mission] ''[[The Times]]'', 24 May 2008</ref>\n\nAlmost all records of the court of inquiry remain unavailable to the public. In 1998, the Navy began declassifying them, but decided in 2012 that it would not release them to the public. In February 2020, in response to a [[FOIA]] lawsuit by military historian James Bryant, a federal court ordered the Navy to begin releasing documents by May 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Eatinger |first1=Robert |title=Fifty-Seven Years Later: America\u2019s Worst Nuclear Submarine Disaster |url=https://www.lawfareblog.com/fifty-seven-years-later-americas-worst-nuclear-submarine-disaster |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=[[Lawfare]] |date=10 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Disaster sequence of 10 April 1963==\n[[File:Ssn593thresher.gif|thumb|right|375px|Time-accelerated sequence of (hypothetical) events during the disaster]]\n[[File:Diagram of depth at Thresher Incident.tif|thumb|A diagram (roughly to scale) of the depth of the ocean where the incident and loss of Thresher took place.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Timeline of the ''Thresher'' disaster<ref>Bentley, John. ''The Thresher Disaster'', New York: Doubleday, 1975, pp. 157\u2013165</ref>\n! Time!!Event\n|-\n| 07:47 || ''Thresher'' begins its descent to the test depth of {{convert|1000|ft|m|abbr=on|order=flip}}.\n|-\n| 07:52 || ''Thresher'' levels off at {{convert|400|ft|m|abbr=on|order=flip}}, contacts the surface, and the crew inspects the ship for leaks. None are found.\n|-\n| 08:09 || Commander Harvey reports reaching half the test depth.\n|-\n| 08:25 || ''Thresher'' reaches {{convert|1000|ft|m|abbr=on|order=flip}}.\n|-\n| 09:02 || ''Thresher'' is cruising at just a few knots (submarines normally move slowly and cautiously at great depths, lest a sudden jam of the diving planes send the ship below test depth in a matter of seconds.) The boat is descending in slow circles, and announces to ''Skylark'' she is turning to \"Corpen [course] 090.\" At this point, transmission quality from ''Thresher'' begins to noticeably degrade, possibly as a result of [[thermocline]]s.\n|-\n| 09:09 || As an unproven hypothesis that is disputed by acoustic data, the Navy's official investigation stated the likelihood of a brazed pipe-joint rupturing in the engine room. The crew would have attempted to stop the leak; at the same time, the engine room would be filling with a cloud of mist. Under the circumstances, Commander Harvey's likely decision would have been to order full speed, full rise on the fairwater planes, and blowing main ballast in order to surface. The pressurized air rapidly expanding in the pipes [[Joule-Thomson effect|cools down]], condensing moisture and depositing it on intended-as temporary strainers installed in the system to protect the moving parts of the valves during new-construction (should have been removed prior to sea trials)<ref>https://www.usni.org/magazines/proceedings/2018/july/declassify-thresher-data</ref>; in only a few seconds the moisture freezes, clogging the strainers and blocking the air flow, halting the effort to blow ballast. Water leaking from the broken pipe most likely causes short circuits leading to an automatic [[scram|shutdown]] of the ship's reactor, causing a loss of propulsion. The logical action at this point would have been for Harvey to order propulsion shifted to a battery-powered backup system. As soon as the flooding was contained, the engine room crew would have begun to restart the reactor, an operation that would be expected to take at least 7&nbsp;minutes.\n|-\n| 09:12 || ''Skylark'' pages ''Thresher'' on the underwater telephone: \"Gertrude [[underwater telephone]] check, K [over].\" With no immediate response (although ''Skylark'' is still unaware of the conditions aboard ''Thresher''), the signal \"K\" is repeated twice.\n|-\n| 09:13 || Harvey reports status via underwater telephone. The transmission is garbled, though some words are recognizable: \"[We are] experiencing minor difficulty, have positive up-angle, attempting to blow.\" The submarine, as a hypothesis, growing heavier from water flooding the engine room, continues its descent, probably tail-first. Another attempt to empty the ballast tanks is performed, again failing due to the formation of ice. Officers on ''Skylark'' could hear the hiss of compressed air over the loudspeaker at this point.\n|-\n| 09:14 || ''Skylark'' acknowledges with a brisk, \"Roger, out,\" awaiting further updates from the SSN. A follow-up message, \"No contacts in area,\" is sent to reassure ''Thresher'' she can surface quickly, without fear of collision, if required.\n|-\n| 09:15 || ''Skylark'' queries ''Thresher'' about her intentions: \"My course 270 degrees. Interrogative range and bearing from you.\" There is no response, and ''Skylark''{{'}}s captain, Lieutenant Commander Hecker, sends his own Gertrude underwater telephone message to the submarine, \"Are you in control?\"\n|-\n| 09:16 || ''Skylark'' picks up a garbled transmission from ''Thresher'', transcribed in the ship's log as \"900 N.\" (The meaning of this message is unclear, and was not discussed at the inquiry; it may have indicated the submarine's depth and course, or it may have referred to a navy \"event number\" (1000 indicating loss of submarine), with the \"N\" signifying a negative response to the query from ''Skylark'', \"Are you in control?\")\n|-\n| 09:17 || A second transmission is received, with the partially recognizable phrase \"exceeding test depth ... \" The (hypothetical) leak from the broken pipe grows with increased pressure.\n|-\n| 09:18 || ''Skylark'' detects a high-energy, low-frequency noise, characteristic of an implosion.\n|-\n| 09:20 || ''Skylark'' continues to page ''Thresher'', repeatedly calling for a radio check, a smoke bomb, or some other indication of the boat's condition.\n|-\n| 11:04 || ''Skylark'' attempts to transmit a message to COMSUBLANT (Commander, Submarines, Atlantic Fleet): \"Unable to communicate with ''Thresher'' since 0917R. Have been calling by [[underwater telephone|UQC]] voice and [[Morse code|CW]], QHB, CW every minute. Explosive signals every 10 minutes with no success. Last transmission received was garbled. Indicated Thresher was approaching test depth ... Conducting expanding search.\" Radio problems meant that COMSUBLANT did not receive and respond to this message until 12:45. Hecker initiated \"Event SUBMISS [loss of a submarine]\" procedures at 11:21, and continued to repeatedly hail ''Thresher'' until after 17:00.\n|}\n\nDuring the 1963 inquiry, Admiral [[Hyman Rickover]] stated:\n\n<blockquote>I believe the loss of the Thresher should not be viewed solely as the result of failure of a specific braze, weld, system or component, but rather should be considered a consequence of the philosophy of design, construction and inspection that has been permitted in our naval shipbuilding programs. I think it is important that we re-evaluate our present practices where, in the desire to make advancements, we may have forsaken the fundamentals of good engineering.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://engineering.vanderbilt.edu/news/2013/vanderbilt-ties-to-%E2%80%98worst-submarine-tragedy%E2%80%99-50-years-ago/ |title=Vanderbilt ties to 'worst submarine tragedy' 50 years ago |publisher=School of Engineering, Vanderbilt University |date=2013 |accessdate=23 April 2013}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Alternative theory of the sinking: electrical failure==\nOn 8 April 2013, Bruce Rule, an acoustic data expert, published his own analysis of the data collected by USS ''Skylark'' and Atlantic [[SOSUS]] arrays in a paper<ref>[http://www.designed4submariners.com/uploads/Docs_Thresher_and_Scorpion_Loss.pdf \"What Sank The Thresher\"], Bruce Rule, 10 April 2013</ref> in the ''Navy Times''.<ref>[http://www.navytimes.com/article/20130404/NEWS/304040021/50-years-later-look-what-really-sank-Thresher \"50 years later, a look at what really sank the ''Thresher''\"], Bruce Rule and [[Norman Polmar]], 4 April 2013 (''Navy Times'' link)</ref><ref name=\"navtimespdf\">[http://www.designed4submariners.com/uploads/Thresher_Report.pdf \"What Sank The Thresher\"], Bruce Rule and [[Norman Polmar]], 8 April 2013</ref> Rule based his analysis on SOSUS data that was highly classified in 1963 and was not discussed in open session of the Court of Inquiry and was not revealed at the congressional hearings.<ref name=\"navtimespdf\"/>  A retired Navy captain and former commanding officer of the same class of submarine as ''Thresher'', citing Rule's findings, has called for the U.S. government to declassify the data associated with the boat's sinking, and presented an alternative disaster sequence based upon the acoustic data.<ref>https://www.usni.org/magazines/proceedings/2018/july/declassify-thresher-data</ref><ref>https://www.kitsapsun.com/story/news/2019/07/16/retired-navy-captain-believes-time-now-release-thresher-records/1738878001/</ref>\n\nRule concluded that the primary cause of the sinking was a failure of the electrical bus that powered the main coolant pumps. According to Rule, SOSUS data indicates that after two minutes of electrical instability, the bus failed at 9:11&nbsp;a.m., causing the main coolant pumps to trip off. This caused an immediate reactor scram, resulting in a loss of propulsion. ''Thresher'' could not be deballasted because ice had formed in the high-pressure air pipes, and so she sank. Rule's analysis holds that flooding (whether from a silver brazed joint or anywhere else) played no role in the reactor scram or the sinking, and that ''Thresher'' was intact until she imploded. In addition to the SOSUS data that does not record any sound of flooding, the crew of ''Skylark'' did not report hearing any noise that sounded like flooding, and ''Skylark'' was able to communicate with ''Thresher'', despite the fact that, at test depth, even a small leak would have produced a deafening roar. Additionally, the previous commander of ''Thresher'' testified that he would not have described flooding, even from a small-diameter pipe, as a \"minor problem\".<ref name=\"navtimespdf\"/>\n\nRule interprets the communication \"900\" from ''Thresher'' at 9:17&nbsp;a.m. as a reference to test depth, signifying that ''Thresher'' was {{convert|900|ft|order=flip}} below her test depth of {{convert|1,300|ft|order=flip}}, or {{convert|2,200|ft|order=flip}} below sea level. According to Rule the SOSUS data indicates an implosion of ''Thresher'' at 09:18:24, at a depth of {{convert|2,400|ft|order=flip}}, {{convert|400|ft|order=flip}} below her predicted collapse depth. The implosion took 0.1 seconds, too fast for the human nervous system to perceive.<ref name=\"navtimespdf\"/>\n\n==SUBSAFE legacy==\nWhen the Court of Inquiry delivered its final report, it recommended that the Navy implement a more rigorous program of design review and safety inspections during construction. That program, launched in December 1963, was known as [[SUBSAFE]]. From 1915 to 1963, the U.S. Navy lost a total of 16 submarines to non-combat accidents. Since the inception of SUBSAFE only one submarine has suffered a similar fate, and that was {{USS|Scorpion|SSN-589|6}}, which sank in 1968 for reasons still undetermined. ''Scorpion'' was not SUBSAFE certified.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seacoastonline.com/articles/20130324-NEWS-303240357 |title=USS Thresher Left Legacy of Safety for Submarines|publisher=SeaCoast online |date=24 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Memorials==\n[[File:6707-ArlingtonCemetary-USS ThresherMemorialStone.png|thumb|right|upright|Memorial stone for a lost USS ''Thresher'' sailor, [[Arlington National Cemetery]], July 1967]]\n[[File:USS_Thresher_memorial_dedication_at_Arlington.jpg|thumb|right|USS ''Thresher'' memorial dedication at [[Arlington National Cemetery]], September 26, 2019]]\n\n=== Permanent ===\n* The chapel at [[Portsmouth Navy Yard]], where the submarine was built, was renamed ''Thresher'' Memorial Chapel.<ref>{{cite book|first=Richard E. |last=Winslow III|title=Portsmouth-Built: Submarines of the Portsmouth Naval Shipyard |page=161|publisher=Portsmouth Marine Society|year=1985|isbn=091581904X}}</ref>\n* In [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire]], there is a stone memorial with a plaque honoring all who were lost on ''Thresher''. It is outside the {{USS|Albacore|AGSS-569|2}} museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WM52XP |title=Wreck of USS Thresher (SSN-593)&nbsp;\u2013 Portsmouth, NH&nbsp;\u2013 Disaster Memorials on |website=Waymarking.com |accessdate=1 June 2010}}</ref>\n* Just outside the main gate of the Naval Weapons Station, [[Seal Beach, California]], a ''Thresher''-''Scorpion'' Memorial honors the crews of the two submarines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.submarinehistory.com/ThresherScorpionMemorial.html |title=ThresherScorpionMemorial |website=Submarinehistory.com |accessdate=1 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100518151910/http://www.submarinehistory.com/ThresherScorpionMemorial.html |archivedate=18 May 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* In [[Eureka, Missouri]], there is a marble stone at the post office on Thresher Drive honoring the \"officers and crew of the USS ''Thresher,'' lost 10 April 1963.\"<ref>[http://www.eureka.mo.us/MINUTES/2007PARK_BOARD/Park_Board_Minutes_4-10-07.pdf Park Board Minutes 04-10-2007] (pdf file) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080626170105/http://www.eureka.mo.us/MINUTES/2007PARK_BOARD/Park_Board_Minutes_4-10-07.pdf |date=26 June 2008}}</ref>\n* [[Salisbury, Massachusetts]], named Robert E. Steinel Memorial Park in honor of ''Thresher'' crewman and Salisbury resident Sonarman First Class Robert Edwin Steinel.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.seacoastonline.com/article/20130120/News/301200337 |title=Thresher victim, a young father, remembered |first=D. Allan |last=Kerr |website=seacoastonline.com |date=January 20, 2013 |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\n* In [[Nutley, New Jersey]], there is a monument to ''Thresher'' crewmember Pervis Robison, Jr.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nutley NJ USS Thresher Memorial|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/sheenachi/145949526/|publisher=Flickr|accessdate=13 August 2016}}</ref>\n* In [[Denville, New Jersey]], there is a monument to ''Thresher'' crewmember Robert D. Kearney at the Gardner Field recreation area.<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert D. Kearney Memorial marker|url=https://www.google.com/maps/@40.8976936,-74.4845036,3a,75y,90t/data=!3m8!1e2!3m6!1s-yhukrjLucZE%2FWSHoH9jyHNI%2FAAAAAAABZXA%2FVTtli-_LA3kVi931pHtIJv9QJBNZ33NZwCLIB!2e4!3e12!6s%2F%2Flh4.googleusercontent.com%2F-yhukrjLucZE%2FWSHoH9jyHNI%2FAAAAAAABZXA%2FVTtli-_LA3kVi931pHtIJv9QJBNZ33NZwCLIB%2Fw203-h270-k-no%2F!7i3024!8i4032|publisher=GoogleMaps|accessdate=21 May 2017}}</ref>\n* Thresher Avenue, named for the submarine, serves a residential area in [[Naval Base Kitsap]] in Washington state.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://goo.gl/maps/XyMALFzNGtn |title=Thresher Ave |website=[[Google Maps]] |accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* A {{convert|129|ft|adj=on}} flagpole at Kittery Memorial Circle in the town of [[Kittery, Maine]], was dedicated on 7 April 2013, the 50th anniversary of the loss of ''Thresher'', to honor the 129 lost souls''.''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kitteryrotaryafterhours.org/thresher-flagpole |title=Thresher Flagpole |website=kitteryrotaryafterhours.org |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\n* There is also a ''Thresher'' monument in Memorial Park next to the Kittery Town Hall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kitteryrotaryafterhours.org/memorial-park|title=Memorial Park|website=kitteryrotaryafterhours.org|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* There is a memorial monument to the submariners lost in the ''Thresher'' and ''Scorpion'' located on Point Pleasant Road in [[Mount Pleasant, South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.https://www.hmdb.org/marker |title=HMdb.org THE HISTORICAL MARKER DATABASE |website=hmdb.org/marker |accessdate=May 30, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Naval Submarine Base New London]] in [[Groton, Connecticut]], named an enlisted barracks \"Thresher Hall\" after the submarine,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.subasect.com/directory/bachelor-housing |title=Bachelor Housing |website=subasect.com |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> and mounted a plaque in its lobby displaying the names of the crew members, shipyard government employees and contractors that were lost.<ref>https://www.ussthresher.com/roster/</ref>{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n* A [[joint resolution]] was introduced during the [[107th United States Congress]] in 2001 calling for the erection of a memorial in [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/uss-thresher.htm|title=USS Thresher Disaster|last=Robert Patterson|first=Michael|website=Arlingtoncemetery.net|accessdate=1 June 2010}}</ref> The formal commemorative monument approval process for Arlington, which began in 2012, received final approval in January 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wmtw.com/article/uss-thresher-memorial-to-be-built-at-arlington-national-cemetery/26073478 |title=USS Thresher memorial to be built at Arlington National Cemetery |website=[[WMTW]] |date=January 29, 2019}}</ref><ref name=fostersJan2019>{{cite news |url=https://www.fosters.com/news/20190129/uss-thresher-memorial-approved-for-arlington-national |title=USS Thresher memorial approved for Arlington National |first=Hadley |last=Barndollar |website=[[Foster's Daily Democrat]] |location=[[Dover, New Hampshire]] |date=January 29, 2019 |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> The memorial was approved on January 28, 2019, by the Secretary of the Army, [[Mark Esper]].<ref>https://threshermemorial.org/</ref> While a few crew members already had memorials at Arlington, this became the first tribute there to the boat's entire crew and her other passengers.<ref name=fostersJan2019/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.usni.org/2019/01/31/army-set-approve-uss-thresher-memorial-arlington-national-cemetery |title=Army Set to Approve USS Thresher Memorial at Arlington National Cemetery |first=John |last=Grady |website=USNI News |date=January 31, 2019}}</ref> The memorial was dedicated on September 26, 2019.<ref name=fostersJanWaPo2019>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/history/2019/09/26/nuclear-submarine-thresher-was-said-be-americas-best-then-tragedy-struck/ |title=The nuclear submarine Thresher was said to be America\u2019s best. Then tragedy struck. |first=Michael E.|last=Ruane|website=[[The Washington Post]] |location=[[Washington, D.C.]] |date=September 26, 2019 |accessdate=September 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fosters.com/news/20190926/tears-in-my-eyes-uss-thresher-memorial-dedicated |title=\u2018Tears in my eyes\u2019: USS Thresher memorial dedicated |first=Trent |last=Spiner |website=[[Foster's Daily Democrat]] |location=[[Dover, New Hampshire]] |date=September 26, 2019 |accessdate=September 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Former\n* In [[Carpentersville, Illinois]], the Dundee Township Park District named a swimming facility (now closed and demolished) in honor of ''Thresher''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dtpd.org/rccms/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/DTPD-Timeline.pdf |title=Brief Timeline of the Dundee Township Park District |website=dtpd.org |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Other ===\n*On 12 April 1963, President [[John F. Kennedy]] issued {{Executive Order|11104}} paying tribute to the crew of ''Thresher'' by ordering all national flags to half-staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051115062550/http://www.lib.umich.edu/govdocs/jfkeo/eo/11104.htm|title=Executive Order 11104|date=15 November 2005|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=22 October 2018}}</ref>\n* Five folk music groups or artists have produced songs memorializing ''Thresher''; \"Ballad Of The Thresher\", by [[The Kingston Trio]], \"The Thresher Disaster\", by [[Tom Paxton]]; \"The Thresher\", by [[Phil Ochs]], \"The Thresher\", by [[Pete Seeger]], and \"Thresher\", by [[Shovels & Rope]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oldsaltblog.com/2013/04/four-ballads-of-the-uss-thresher/ |title=Four Ballads of the USS Thresher |first=Rick |last=Spilman |website=oldsaltblog.com |date=April 14, 2013 |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2014/08/17/339586770/first-listen-shovels-rope-swimmin-time |title=First Listen: Shovels & Rope, 'Swimmin' Time'|first=Ann |last=Powers |website=npr.org |date=August 17, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Deep Submergence Rescue Vehicle]]\n* {{USS|Scorpion|SSN-589}}, the only other American nuclear-powered submarine to be lost at sea\n* [[John P. Craven]], a key individual in the search for ''Thresher''\n* [[Kursk submarine disaster|''Kursk'' submarine disaster]], next largest loss of life on a submarine\n* [[List of sunken nuclear submarines]]\n* [[List of lost United States submarines]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* One of the earliest and most comprehensive accounts of the loss of the ''Thresher'' was written by Vice Admiral E.W. Grenfell, Commander Submarine Force Atlantic, and published in March 1964 in the U.S. Navy's professional journal ''Proceedings''; on 1 April 2013, on the occasion of the 50th anniversary, the U.S. Naval Institute has re-posted Admiral Grenfell's detailed account: {{cite web|url=http://www.navalhistory.org/2013/04/01/uss-thresher-ssn-593-3-august-1961-10-april-1963|title=USS Thresher (SSN-593) 3 August 1961 \u2013 10 April 1963}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040804224339/http://www.submarinehistory.com/Thresher.html Loss of USS ''Thresher'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100518151910/http://www.submarinehistory.com/ThresherScorpionMemorial.html ''Thresher-Scorpion'' Memorial]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110927013845/http://www.submarinehistory.com/WWIISubmarineMemorial.html World War II National Submarine Memorial&nbsp;\u2013 West]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110927013857/http://www.submarinehistory.com/WWIISubmarineMemorial-East.html World War II National Submarine Memorial&nbsp;\u2013 East]\n* {{cite book |last=Sontag |first=Sherry |first2= Christopher|last2= Drew|first3=Annette Lawrence |last3=Drew |title=[[Blind Man's Bluff: The Untold Story of American Submarine Espionage]] |publisher=HarperPaperbacks |location=New York |year=1999 |isbn=0-06-103004-X}}\n* {{cite book |last=Polmar |first=Norman |authorlink=Norman Polmar |title=Death of the Thresher |publisher=Chilton Books |location=Philadelphia |year=1964 |isbn=1-58574-348-8 |url=https://archive.org/details/deathofussthresh00norm }} First published 1964; reissued in 2001 by Lyons Press (Guilford, Conn) as ''The Death of the USS Thresher''\n* {{cite book |last=Bentley |first=John |title=The Thresher Disaster: The Most Tragic Dive in Submarine History |publisher=Doubleday |location=Garden City, N.Y |year=1975 |isbn=0-385-03057-6 |url=https://archive.org/details/thresherdisaster00bent }}\n* {{cite book |last=Rockwell |first=Theodore |title=The Rickover Effect: How One Man made a Difference |publisher=IUniverse |location=Lincoln |year=2002 |isbn=0-595-74527-X }}\n* [https://archive.is/20130201132002/http://archiver.rootsweb.com/th/read/USS-THRESHER-SSN593/2005-01/1104944120 McCoole's statement re: shutting main steam valves during reactor scram]\n* {{cite book|last=DiMercurio|first=Michael|title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to Submarines|year=2003|publisher=Alpha Books |location=Indianapolis|isbn=978-0-02-864471-4|last2=Benson|first2=Michael}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author=Joint Committee on Atomic Energy (United States Congress)|title=Loss of the U.S.S. \"Thresher\": Hearings, Eighty-eighth Congress, first and second sessions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uKAJmmtgIUEC|accessdate=5 April 2013|year=1965 |publisher=Govt. Print. Off.}}\n* U.S. Atlantic Fleet. Staff, Deputy Commander Submarine Force. (1964) United States Ship Thresher (SSN 593): In memoriam 10 April 1963. U.S. Navy Atlantic Fleet. No Available ISBN.\n* ''Thresher''{{'}}s ship number 593 is interesting as a \"good\" prime number, as discussed at [[593 (number)|593]].\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|USS Thresher (SSN-593)}}\n* [http://www.oneternalpatrol.com/uss-thresher-593.htm On Eternal Patrol: USS ''Thresher'']\n* [http://www.navsource.org/archives/08/08593.htm Photo gallery of ''Thresher'' at NavSource.org]\n* http://www.ussthresher.com/\n* http://www.thresherbase.org/\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r0bRA1hp23w Memorial Video on YouTube]\n\n{{Permit class submarine}}\n{{1963 shipwrecks}}\n{{coord|41|46|N|65|03|W|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thresher (Ssn-593)}}\n[[Category:United States submarine accidents]]\n[[Category:Permit-class submarines]]\n[[Category:Cold War submarines of the United States]]\n[[Category:Lost submarines of the United States]]\n[[Category:Sunken nuclear submarines]]\n[[Category:Nuclear submarines of the United States Navy|Thresher, USS]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1963]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks in the Atlantic Ocean|Thresher, USS]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Kittery, Maine]]\n[[Category:1960 ships]]\n[[Category:1963 in the United States]]\n[[Category:Ships lost with all hands]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCause", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USS_Thresher_(SSN-593)"}
{"title_page": "Hotline Communications", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Hotline Communications Limited\n| logo = Hotline Communications Logo - 200px.png\n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = The logo for Hotline Communications, once dubbed \"the best kept secret\" on the internet by the L.A. Times\n| logo_caption = The logo for Hotline Communications, once dubbed \"the best kept secret\" on the internet by the L.A. Times\n| logo_padding = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. For multiple names in different languages, use {{lang|[code]|[name]}}. -->\n| former_name = \n| type = \n| industry = \n| founded = <!-- if known: {{start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} in [[city]], [[state]], [[country]] -->\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| hq_location = \n| hq_location_city = \n| hq_location_country = \n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people = \n| products = \n| brands = \n| services = \n| owner = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| ratio = <!-- for BANKS ONLY -->\n| rating = <!-- for BANKS ONLY -->\n| website = <!-- or: | homepage = --><!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''Hotline Communications Limited''' (HCL) was a [[software company]] founded in 1997, based in [[Toronto]], Canada, with employees also in the United States and Australia. Hotline Communications' main activity was the publishing and distribution of a multi-purpose client/server [[communication software]] product named ''Hotline Connect'', informally called, simply, ''Hotline''. Initially, Hotline Communications sought a wide audience for its products, and organizations as diverse as [[Avid Technology]], [[Apple Inc.|Apple Computer Australia]], and public high schools used Hotline. At its peak, Hotline received millions of dollars in [[venture capital]] funding, grew to employ more than fifty people, served millions of users, and won accolades at trade shows and in newspapers and computer magazines around the world.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n\nHotline eventually attracted more of an \"underground\" community,{{clarify|date=April 2012}} which saw it as an easier to use successor to the [[Internet Relay Chat]] (IRC) community.  Shortly after the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]],{{elucidate|date=April 2012}} Hotline Communications lost the bulk of its VC funding, and went out of business later that month.  All of its assets were acquired in 2002 by ''Hotsprings, Inc.'', a new company formed by some ex-employees and [[shareholders]]. Hotsprings Inc. has since also abandoned development of the Hotline Connect software suite; the last iteration of ''Hotline Connect'' was released in December 2003. Currently, only a few servers and trackers remain but the Hotline community is still alive.\n\n==History==\nHotline was designed in 1996 and known as \"hotwire\" by Australian programmer [[Adam Hinkley]] (known online by his username, \"Hinks\"), then 17 years old, as a [[classic Mac OS]] application. The [[source code]] for the Hotline applications was based on a class library, \"AppWarrior\" (AW), which Hinkley wrote. AppWarrior would later become litigious, as Hinkley wrote parts of it while he was employed by an Australian company, Redrock Holdings. Six other fans of Hotline, David Murphy, Alex King, Phil Hilton, Jason Roks, David Bordin, and Terrance Gregory, joined Adam Hinkley's efforts to promote and market the Hotline programs, working day and night and using the company's own products to stay in touch from across the US, Canada, and Australia. Eventually, Canadian Jason Roks approached Adam Hinkley and encouraged him to move to Toronto, where Hotline Communications, Ltd. was incorporated. In 1997, ''Hotline'' won a \"Best of the Show\" award from one of the award ceremonies concurrent with the Boston [[MacWorld Expo]]. It received accolades in computer magazines and the mainstream press from ''Macworld Sweden'' (which awarded it a \"Golden Mouse Award\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.macworld.se/Guldmusen97.html |title=Guldmusen 1997 |date=June 1997 |publisher=MacWorld Sweden |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000605030540/http://www.macworld.se/Guldmusen97.html |archive-date=5 June 2000}}</ref>) to the ''Los Angeles Times'', which called it one of the \"best kept secrets on the internet\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/feb/22/news/tt-28765 |title=Napster Leads, but What Follows Works |last=Wilson |first=Dave |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=22 February 2001 |access-date=16 June 2015}}</ref> as well as a short article in [[Wired (magazine)|Wired Magazine]]'s September 1997 issue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.wired.com/science/discoveries/news/1997/09/6945 |title=Street Cred: Hot Connection |last=Cockwell |first=Andrew |publisher=Wired |date=17 September 1997 |access-date=16 June 2015}}</ref> At the time, the company's main objective was to release a stable [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]]-compatible version to reach a wider audience.\n\nHowever, a few months after Hinkley moved to Canada, he and his colleagues at Hotline Communications got into a major disagreement and Hinkley left the firm, encrypting source files for ''Hotline'' on Hotline Communication's computers, thus crippling the company. Lawsuits against Hinkley were filed by both Hotline Communications and Redrock, and Hinkley lost copyright of his \"AppWarrior\" library as well as rights over the \"Hotline\" software. The legal battle and Hinkley's case drew some media attention, especially on the Internet.\n\nIn the late 1990s, when Hotline's popularity was at its peak, thousands of Hotline servers were available, catering to a wide variety of user interests, including pornography, MP3s, and pirated software; it was these underground purposes that drew the majority of media attention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macworld.com/article/2031816/hotline-revisited.html|title=Hotline revisited: The early internet|date=March 30, 2013|website=Macworld}}</ref> To access these files most Hotline servers required a login and password. The password was often obtainable by visiting a website provided by the server admin and clicking on a banner advertisement. Server admins would earn money per click and in return offer pirated software, music, movies and pornography to users.\n\nAt the end of the 1990s, by then outdated Hotline software started to gradually fade, as [[peer-to-peer]] systems like [[Gnutella]] and [[Kazaa]] became increasingly popular. Many early Hotline users felt sympathy for Hinkley and viewed Hotline Communications with a bad eye and the Hotline Connect suite did not sell well.  In September 2001, Hotline Communications announced development of version 2.0 of the Hotline suite had been stopped, beta versions of which had not been well received by the community, and laid off most of its employees. In mid-October of the same year, the company announced the re-hire of their engineering team \"in anticipation of the release of Hotline 2.0\" on their website<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smarthomeradar.com/hotline-communications/|title=Hotline Communications (BigredH) - The first social media innovators|date=December 16, 2019}}</ref> (offline as of May 2006). However, no stable build  of Hotline 2.0 was ever released.\n\nAs of April 2020, tracked.stickytack.com and hltracker.com continue to provide tracker services for Hotline clients.<ref>Up to date whois information.</ref>\n\n==Hotline Connect software suite==\n[[File:hotline.png|thumb|Many ''Hotline Server'' users did not have a fixed IP address; Hotline clients users can browse server lists by accessing \"trackers\", machines with fixed IPs that keep track of the IPs of online servers.]]\n\nThe Hotline applications were distributed as [[shareware]] and combined [[online chat|chat]], [[message board]] and file transfer capabilities and operated using a client/server (not peer-to-peer) model.  Hotline predates the [[Napster]] and [[Gnutella]] file sharing products. The Hotline protocol was a [[binary protocol]] which accounted for its high speed efficient transfers in the days when most internet users still used [[modem]]s and [[dialup]]. The protocol was [[reverse engineered]] by the [[internet community]], leading to a wide variety of third-party clients being written in [[RealBasic]], one of the few easy-to-use development environments available on the Macintosh at the time.\n\n''Hotline Connect'' consisted of three applications, distributed separately (via Internet download or on promotional CDs):\n* '''Hotline Client''': an application used to access ''Hotline'' [[server (computing)|servers]] set up by users running the ''Hotline Server'' software. Hotline Connect users with a client installed could connect to servers they knew using the [[server (computing)|host]]'s IP address.\n* '''Hotline Server''': an easy-to-configure server application.\n* '''Hotline Tracker''': a name server, used to keep track of the IP addresses of several ''Hotline'' servers.\n\n==Hotline successors==\nA company named Haxial Software (rumored to be Adam Hinkley){{citation needed|date=July 2018}} released a Hotline-like product named KDX.\n\nJ\u00f6rn and Mirko Hartmann released similar software deliberately kept Mac-only called [[Carracho]] in 1998 Carracho GbR - Welcome, still used today by a small, tight-knit group of users. There have also been several third-party applications that implement the Hotline protocol.\n\nThere have been several open-source versions of the Hotline Client and Server suite, which were not based on the official source code, and provide several protocol enhancements (also known as HOPE - HOtline Protocol Extension).\nSome versions also support an [[Internet Relay Chat|IRC]] bridge or KDX bridge. Most of the work on the Hotline enhancements have been done by r0r (HOPE, KDX), kang (IRC) and Devin Teske. See <!--[[KDX (software)|KDX]], and -->[[Darknet]] for details.\n\nHotline's largest community Mixed Blood, started by Prime Chuck and SAINT in 1998, is still active to this day on Wired. Wired is similar to Hotline and developed by [[Zanka software]].\n\nAnother very large hotline server of the same time, Not All Mine, or notallmine.net, converted to HTML format and went private around 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050915000000*/http://notallmine.net|title=Wayback Machine|date=September 15, 2005|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\n==Modern clients (constantly being updated)==\n* Pitbull Pro, a remake of the original OS9/X client (Windows)\n\n==Open source clients==\n* Fidelio - open-source Hotline client, no longer updated since 2002 (Linux/Unix)\n* mhxd - open-source Hotline server and client\n* synhxd - open-source Hotline server and client\n* gtkhx - open-source Hotline client, no longer updated since 2001 (Linux/Unix)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{More footnotes|date=January 2009}}\n'''Company and product history'''\n* \"[https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://bigredh.com Wayback Machine search results for 'bigredh.com']\", ''[[Internet Archive]] Wayback Machine''. Accessed on April 7, 2005. \u2014 A chronicle of the different versions of the bigredh.com website. \"BigRedH.com\" was Hotline Communication's website and e-commerce platform from June 2001 on. [[E-commerce]] \"service provider\" [[Digital River]] designed the original website ([https://web.archive.org/web/20050312050041/http://drhome.digitalriver.com/livehtml/newsite/pr_201.html Digital River press release]).\n* \"[https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://hotspringsinc.com Wayback Machine search results for 'hotspringsinc.com']\", ''Internet Archive Wayback Machine''. Accessed on April 7, 2005. \u2014 A chronicle of the different versions of the hotspringsinc.com website.\n* \"[http://www.macworld.com/article/2031816/hotline-revisited.html Macworld Hotline Revisited Article]\n* \"[http://omgwtfbbq.ca/2015/07/hotline-the-glory-days-of-p2p/ Hotline \u2013 The Glory Days of P2P]\"\n\n'''Legal battle'''\n* \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20090113145012/http://archive.salon.com/21st/feature/1999/02/25feature.html Hotline's Civil War]\" (broken link), ''Salon.com Archive''. Accessed on April 3, 2005.\n* \"[http://www.abc.net.au/rn/talks/8.30/lawrpt/stories/s295800.htm Employment Law, Intellectual Property Law and the New Economy]\" (radio program transcript), ''The Law Report'' ([http://www.abc.net.au/rn/talks/8.30/lawrpt/default.htm website]), Australian Broadcasting Corporation Radio National ([http://www.abc.net.au/rn/default.htm website]). Accessed April 7, 2005. \u2014 Discussion of the ''Hotline vs. Hinkley'' legal battle in the broader context of intellectual property law in Australia.\n* \"[http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=01/04/09/1639212&mode=thread Adam Hinkley's IP Hindsights]\", ''Slashdot.org''. Accessed on April 7, 2005. \u2014 Slashdot discussion about original ''Hotline'' programmer Adam Hinkley's legal battle against his former Hotline Communications, Ltd. associates.\n* \"[http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/cases/vic/VSC/2001/91.html Redrock Holdings Pty Ltd & Hotline Communications Ltd & Ors v Hinkley (2001) VSC 91 (4 April 2001)]\", Text of the 2001 Victoria Supreme Court judgement assigning ownership of Hotline Connect to Hotline Communications.\n\n[[Category:Defunct software companies]]\n[[Category:Online chat]]\n[[Category:Internet forums]]\n[[Category:File sharing communities]]\n[[Category:File sharing networks]]\n[[Category:1997 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Canadian companies established in 1997]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Hotline Communications Limited\n| logo = Hotline Communications Logo - 200px.png\n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = The logo for Hotline Communications, once dubbed \"the best kept secret\" on the internet by the L.A. Times\n| logo_caption = The logo for Hotline Communications, once dubbed \"the best kept secret\" on the internet by the L.A. Times\n| logo_padding = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. For multiple names in different languages, use {{lang|[code]|[name]}}. -->\n| former_name = \n| type = \n| industry = \n| founded = <!-- if known: {{start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} in [[city]], [[state]], [[country]] -->\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| hq_location = \n| hq_location_city = \n| hq_location_country = \n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people = \n| products = \n| brands = \n| services = \n| owner = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| ratio = <!-- for BANKS ONLY -->\n| rating = <!-- for BANKS ONLY -->\n| website = <!-- or: | homepage = --><!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''Hotline Communications Limited''' (HCL) was a [[software company]] founded in 1997, based in [[Toronto]], Canada, with employees also in the United States and Australia. Hotline Communications' main activity was the publishing and distribution of a multi-purpose client/server [[communication software]] product named ''Hotline Connect'', informally called, simply, ''Hotline''. Initially, Hotline Communications sought a wide audience for its products, and organizations as diverse as [[Avid Technology]], [[Apple Inc.|Apple Computer Australia]], and public high schools used Hotline. At its peak, Hotline received millions of dollars in [[venture capital]] funding, grew to employ more than fifty people, served millions of users, and won accolades at trade shows and in newspapers and computer magazines around the world.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n\nHotline eventually attracted more of an \"underground\" community,{{clarify|date=April 2012}} which saw it as an easier to use successor to the [[Internet Relay Chat]] (IRC) community.  Shortly after the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]],{{elucidate|date=April 2012}} Hotline Communications lost the bulk of its VC funding, and went out of business later that month.  All of its assets were acquired in 2002 by ''Hotsprings, Inc.'', a new company formed by some ex-employees and [[shareholders]]. Hotsprings Inc. has since also abandoned development of the Hotline Connect software suite; the last iteration of ''Hotline Connect'' was released in December 2003. Currently, only a few servers and trackers remain but the Hotline community is still alive.\n\n==History==\nHotline was designed in 1996 and known as \"hotwire\" by Australian programmer [[Adam Hinkley]] (known online by his username, \"Hinks\"), then 17 years old, as a [[classic Mac OS]] application. The [[source code]] for the Hotline applications was based on a class library, \"AppWarrior\" (AW), which Hinkley wrote. AppWarrior would later become litigious, as Hinkley wrote parts of it while he was employed by an Australian company, Redrock Holdings. Six other fans of Hotline, David Murphy, Alex King, Phil Hilton, Jason Roks, David Bordin, and Terrance Gregory, joined Adam Hinkley's efforts to promote and market the Hotline programs, working day and night and using the company's own products to stay in touch from across the USA, Canada, and Australia. Eventually, Canadian Jason Roks approached Adam Hinkley and encouraged him to move to Toronto, where Hotline Communications, Ltd. was incorporated. In 1997, ''Hotline'' won a \"Best of the Show\" award from one of the award ceremonies concurrent with the Boston [[MacWorld Expo]]. It received accolades in computer magazines and the mainstream press from ''Macworld Sweden'' (which awarded it a \"Golden Mouse Award\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.macworld.se/Guldmusen97.html |title=Guldmusen 1997 |date=June 1997 |publisher=MacWorld Sweden |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000605030540/http://www.macworld.se/Guldmusen97.html |archive-date=5 June 2000}}</ref>) to the ''Los Angeles Times'', which called it one of the \"best kept secrets on the internet\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/feb/22/news/tt-28765 |title=Napster Leads, but What Follows Works |last=Wilson |first=Dave |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=22 February 2001 |access-date=16 June 2015}}</ref> as well as a short article in [[Wired (magazine)|Wired Magazine]]'s September 1997 issue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.wired.com/science/discoveries/news/1997/09/6945 |title=Street Cred: Hot Connection |last=Cockwell |first=Andrew |publisher=Wired |date=17 September 1997 |access-date=16 June 2015}}</ref> At the time, the company's main objective was to release a stable [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]]-compatible version to reach a wider audience.\n\nHowever, a few months after Hinkley moved to Canada, he and his colleagues at Hotline Communications got into a major disagreement and Hinkley left the firm, encrypting source files for ''Hotline'' on Hotline Communication's computers, thus crippling the company. Lawsuits against Hinkley were filed by both Hotline Communications and Redrock, and Hinkley lost copyright of his \"AppWarrior\" library as well as rights over the \"Hotline\" software. The legal battle and Hinkley's case drew some media attention, especially on the Internet.\n\nIn the late 1990s, when Hotline's popularity was at its peak, thousands of Hotline servers were available, catering to a wide variety of user interests, including pornography, MP3s, and pirated software; it was these underground purposes that drew the majority of media attention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macworld.com/article/2031816/hotline-revisited.html|title=Hotline revisited: The early internet|date=March 30, 2013|website=Macworld}}</ref> To access these files most Hotline servers required a login and password. The password was often obtainable by visiting a website provided by the server admin and clicking on a banner advertisement. Server admins would earn money per click and in return offer pirated software, music, movies and pornography to users.\n\nAt the end of the 1990s, by then outdated Hotline software started to gradually fade, as [[peer-to-peer]] systems like [[Gnutella]] and [[Kazaa]] became increasingly popular. Many early Hotline users felt sympathy for Hinkley and viewed Hotline Communications with a bad eye and the Hotline Connect suite did not sell well.  In September 2001, Hotline Communications announced development of version 2.0 of the Hotline suite had been stopped, beta versions of which had not been well received by the community, and laid off most of its employees. In mid-October of the same year, the company announced the re-hire of their engineering team \"in anticipation of the release of Hotline 2.0\" on their website<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smarthomeradar.com/hotline-communications/|title=Hotline Communications (BigredH) - The first social media innovators|date=December 16, 2019}}</ref> (offline as of May 2006). However, no stable build  of Hotline 2.0 was ever released.\n\nAs of April 2020, tracked.stickytack.com and hltracker.com continue to provide tracker services for Hotline clients.<ref>Up to date whois information.</ref>\n\n==Hotline Connect software suite==\n[[File:hotline.png|thumb|Many ''Hotline Server'' users did not have a fixed IP address; Hotline clients users can browse server lists by accessing \"trackers\", machines with fixed IPs that keep track of the IPs of online servers.]]\n\nThe Hotline applications were distributed as [[shareware]] and combined [[online chat|chat]], [[message board]] and file transfer capabilities and operated using a client/server (not peer-to-peer) model.  Hotline predates the [[Napster]] and [[Gnutella]] file sharing products. The Hotline protocol was a [[binary protocol]] which accounted for its high speed efficient transfers in the days when most internet users still used [[modem]]s and [[dialup]]. The protocol was [[reverse engineered]] by the [[internet community]], leading to a wide variety of third-party clients being written in [[RealBasic]], one of the few easy-to-use development environments available on the Macintosh at the time.\n\n''Hotline Connect'' consisted of three applications, distributed separately (via Internet download or on promotional CDs):\n* '''Hotline Client''': an application used to access ''Hotline'' [[server (computing)|servers]] set up by users running the ''Hotline Server'' software. Hotline Connect users with a client installed could connect to servers they knew using the [[server (computing)|host]]'s IP address.\n* '''Hotline Server''': an easy-to-configure server application.\n* '''Hotline Tracker''': a name server, used to keep track of the IP addresses of several ''Hotline'' servers.\n\n==Hotline successors==\nA company named Haxial Software (rumored to be Adam Hinkley){{cn|date=July 2018}} released a Hotline-like product named KDX.\n\nJ\u00f6rn and Mirko Hartmann released similar software deliberately kept Mac-only called [[Carracho]] in 1998 Carracho GbR - Welcome, still used today by a small, tight-knit group of users. There have also been several third-party applications that implement the Hotline protocol.\n\nThere have been several open-source versions of the Hotline Client and Server suite, which were not based on the official source code, and provide several protocol enhancements (also known as HOPE - HOtline Protocol Extension).\nSome versions also support an [[Internet Relay Chat|IRC]] bridge or KDX bridge. Most of the work on the Hotline enhancements have been done by r0r (HOPE, KDX), kang (IRC) and Devin Teske. See <!--[[KDX (software)|KDX]], and -->[[Darknet]] for details.\n\nHotline's largest community Mixed Blood, started by Prime Chuck and SAINT in 1998, is still active to this day on Wired. Wired is similar to Hotline and developed by [[Zanka software]].\n\nAnother very large hotline server of the same time, Not All Mine, or notallmine.net, converted to HTML format and went private around 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050915000000*/http://notallmine.net|title=Wayback Machine|date=September 15, 2005|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\n==Modern clients (constantly being updated)==\n* Pitbull Pro, a remake of the original OS9/X client (Windows)\n\n==Open source clients==\n* Fidelio - open-source Hotline client, no longer updated since 2002 (Linux/Unix)\n* mhxd - open-source Hotline server and client\n* synhxd - open-source Hotline server and client\n* gtkhx - open-source Hotline client, no longer updated since 2001 (Linux/Unix)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{More footnotes|date=January 2009}}\n'''Company and product history'''\n* \"[https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://bigredh.com Wayback Machine search results for 'bigredh.com']\", ''[[Internet Archive]] Wayback Machine''. Accessed on April 7, 2005. \u2014 A chronicle of the different versions of the bigredh.com website. \"BigRedH.com\" was Hotline Communication's website and e-commerce platform from June 2001 on. [[E-commerce]] \"service provider\" [[Digital River]] designed the original website ([https://web.archive.org/web/20050312050041/http://drhome.digitalriver.com/livehtml/newsite/pr_201.html Digital River press release]).\n* \"[https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://hotspringsinc.com Wayback Machine search results for 'hotspringsinc.com']\", ''Internet Archive Wayback Machine''. Accessed on April 7, 2005. \u2014 A chronicle of the different versions of the hotspringsinc.com website.\n* \"[http://www.macworld.com/article/2031816/hotline-revisited.html Macworld Hotline Revisited Article]\n* \"[http://omgwtfbbq.ca/2015/07/hotline-the-glory-days-of-p2p/ Hotline \u2013 The Glory Days of P2P]\"\n\n'''Legal battle'''\n* \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20090113145012/http://archive.salon.com/21st/feature/1999/02/25feature.html Hotline's Civil War]\" (broken link), ''Salon.com Archive''. Accessed on April 3, 2005.\n* \"[http://www.abc.net.au/rn/talks/8.30/lawrpt/stories/s295800.htm Employment Law, Intellectual Property Law and the New Economy]\" (radio program transcri